<DIV1 TYPE="appendix">
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="[185]">
<HEAD>Anhang.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. Noch unbekannte Versionen von den Stoffen der Kildare-Gedichte.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="poems">
<HEAD>I. Die Zehn Gebote und die Sieben Tods&uuml;nden.</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="manuscript source">
<HEAD>A. Ms. Laud 463 (fr&uuml;her Laud 70)</HEAD>
<DIV5 TYPE="editorial note">
<P>Legendenhandschrift aus dem Anfang des 15. Jahrhunderts, Pergament. Horstmann hat aus dieser Handschrift Anglia I, p. 55 ff. die durch ihren Strophenbau bemerkenswerte Legende Celestin abgedruckt und dabei auch einige Bemerkungen &uuml;ber die Schreibung des Ms. gegeben. Die Sieben Tods&uuml;nden und die Zehn Gebote des Laud Ms. sind ebenso wie die nordengl. Version in kurzen Reimpaaren abgefa&szlig;t und geh&ouml;ren zu den interessantesten Erzeugnissen dieser Art, welche schon &auml;u&szlig;erlich der Kildare-Version verh&auml;ltnism&auml;&szlig;ig nahe steht; der Hauptteil des Ms. stellt sich zu dem s&uuml;denglischen Legendencyklus.</P><P>Die Schn&ouml;rkel an <I>k</I> und <I>g, t</I> und <I>d</I> (<I>k<GAP>, g<GAP>, t<GAP>, d<GAP></I>) sind nicht be|r&uuml;cksichtigt, da sie sich &auml;hnlich sogar an -<I>e</I> befinden, z. B. <I>&thorn;e<GAP>, he<GAP>, ne<GAP>.</I>In den Texten ist <GAP> am Wortende als <I>es</I> aufgel&ouml;st, z. B. <I>tusk<GAP> = tuskes</I>, dagegen ist der Strich, der sich gew&ouml;hnlich in auslaut. <I>ll</I> findet (<I>ll</I>), nicht ber&uuml;cksichtigt; Striche &uuml;ber <I>m, n,</I> da wo nicht Doppelkonsonanz be|absichtigt sein kann, sind beibehalten (z. B. <I>vpon</I>).</P></DIV5>
<DIV5 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Septem peccata mortalia.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Iesu, &thorn;at wolde for vs dye<MILESTONE N="157" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And was boren of mayde Marie,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue hem alle his blessing</L>
<L>&THORN;at wole here &thorn;is talking,
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="186"></L>
<L>To helpe &thorn;e sely soule to liuen</L>
<L>&THORN;at Iesu Crist vs ha&thorn; &yogh;euen.</L>
<L>&THORN;er beo dedly sinnes seue&ntilde;</L>
<L>&THORN;at letten men to com to heue&ntilde;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;at leouen in godes lore,</L>
<L>Of twelue winter old or more,</L>
<L>Euerichon &thorn;ei sholde knowe,</L>
<L>Bot to lerne &thorn;ei beon to slowe.</L>
<L>Liste&thorn; nouh bo&thorn;e &yogh;ong and olde,</L>
<L>And &yogh;e shole here smertly hem tolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>At pride first I wile begynne,</L>
<L>For it is hed of al oure sinne.</L>
<L>Grete lordes wi&thorn; londes and ledes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at riden vpon gret stedes,</L>
<L>Clad in purpre and in pall,</L>
<L>In taffata and in sendall,</L>
<L>Castelles, halles and chambres wide &mdash;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is telle&thorn; god no pride,</L>
<L>&THORN;at man may wi&thorn; treuthe winne.</L>
<L>To liue wi&thorn; honour &thorn;at is no sinne</L>
<L>In loue and in gode lyf,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; oute contek, wi&thorn; oute strif.</L>
<L>Bot he &thorn;at ha&thorn; londes wide</L>
<L>And maigtene&thorn; ouer gret pride</L>
<L>And pile&thorn; his pore men &thorn;er fore</L>
<L>To paie for pride &thorn;at ha&thorn; he lore,</L>
<L>And falseliche winne&thorn; londes and ledes</L>
<L>To mayntene his dedes</L>
<L>In liking of worldly winne &mdash;</L>
<L>Suche pride is dedly sinne.</L>
<L>&THORN;is is a foule pride ywis,</L>
<L>And an o&thorn;er pride &thorn;er is</L>
<L>Among men of lasse catel,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &yogh;e shole here wel.</L>
<L>If a man for enuie</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at he seo&thorn; wi&thorn; his eye</L>
<L>&THORN;at his neigheboure beo</L>
<L>Better atired &thorn;an he</L>
<L>And telle&thorn; of him self so myche</L>
<L>And atire&thorn; him richeliche,
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="187"></L>
<L>Riccher &thorn;an his auenant is,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto winne&thorn; catel amys</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; falsdam and trecherie</L>
<L>To meyntene his herte hye &mdash;</L>
<L>Of suche pride, as &thorn;at is,</L>
<L>God nis not paied ywis.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ei a man after his myht</L>
<L>Beo clanliche clothed and dyght</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at he may wi&thorn; treuthe winne,</L>
<L>Suche pride is no sinne.</L>
<L>God wile &thorn;at eche creature</L>
<L>Be his poer his body honoure,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at he despise nothing</L>
<L>Him &thorn;at is in pore clothing.</L>
<L>If he despise any wight</L>
<L>&THORN;at is poreliche ydight,</L>
<L>&THORN;anne do&thorn; he amys,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at is sinne and pride ywis.</L>
<L>And an o&thorn;er poynt &thorn;er is</L>
<L>In pouert pride ywis.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei a man haue nought,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et he may beo proud in thouht</L>
<L>And wilne to winne &thorn;ing amis,</L>
<L>To make him prodder &thorn;an he is,</L>
<L>And &thorn;oruh thouht and wikke wille</L>
<L>&THORN;e sely soule he may spille.</L>
<L>Wite eche riche man him &thorn;erfro,</L>
<L>Pride wirke&thorn; man ful wo.</L>
<L>Be Lucifer a man may wite,</L>
<L>Fo[r] pride, &thorn;at in him was smyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mychel ioye of heuen he les</L>
<L>And &thorn;e pyne of helle he chees.</L>
<L>Alto long it were to bide</L>
<L>To telle &thorn;e wo &thorn;at come&thorn; of pride.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou haue &yogh;e herd a partye,</L>
<L>Nou shul &yogh;e here of glotonye.</L>
<L>It is no glotony ywis<MILESTONE N="157b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To ete and drink, whan tyme is,</L>
<L>For god almyhty him self wile</L>
<L>&THORN;at man ete ynouh be skile.
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="188"></L>
<L>Man &thorn;at swinke&thorn; and do&thorn; his dede</L>
<L>May ete as ofte, as he ha&thorn; nede;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at ete&thorn; for coueityse</L>
<L>And drink so myche, er he arise,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wolnot wone his body wi&thorn; inne &mdash;</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e &thorn;at is dedly sinne.</L>
<L>And a man &thorn;at ha&thorn; his hele</L>
<L>And mete ynouh at a mele,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er begged o&thorn;er bouht,</L>
<L>And is ydel and swinke&thorn; nought</L>
<L>And on fasting day ete twie &mdash;</L>
<L>Forsothe &thorn;at is glotonye.</L>
<L>A man &thorn;at swat not ne swinke&thorn;</L>
<L>And atte tauerne sit and drinke&thorn;</L>
<L>Before mete and in his wille,</L>
<L>Of wyn or ale his body to fille,</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e he ne faste&thorn; nought,</L>
<L>He breke&thorn; his fast in &thorn;at thought.</L>
<L>A poynt of glotonye &thorn;is is,</L>
<L>And &yogh;et &thorn;er beon mo ywis.</L>
<L>Who so is alday wel dyght</L>
<L>And ete in vntyme be nyght,</L>
<L>He shent godes creature</L>
<L>&THORN;at sholde liuen in mesure,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he li&thorn; in glotonye</L>
<L>And do&thorn; &thorn;e soule gret vilenye</L>
<L>And waste&thorn; &thorn;at o&thorn;ere myght ete</L>
<L>&THORN;at hauen gret defaute of mete.</L>
<L>Who so delite&thorn; him &thorn;er inne,</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e it is a dedly sinne.</L>
<L>And who so ha&thorn; drink and mete</L>
<L>And anon after &thorn;at mete</L>
<L>Atte tauerne so long sit,</L>
<L>Til him ginne to wante wit,</L>
<L>And wile &thorn;anne contek beginne &mdash;</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e &thorn;at is dedly sinne.</L>
<L>An o&thorn;er glotonye &thorn;er is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle men knowe not ywis.</L>
<L>Atte &thorn;e mete, if he beo</L>
<L>And he may here and seo
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="189"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his ere and wi&thorn; his eye</L>
<L>A pore man for honger crye,</L>
<L>Man &thorn;at ete&thorn; and drinke&thorn; his fille</L>
<L>And let &thorn;e pore man stonde stille</L>
<L>And myhte helpe him and nille &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy bok shewe&thorn; it be skille:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is glotonye and sinne,</L>
<L>Suche lyf who so is inne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Long it were forto dwelle,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e articles forto telle</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er come&thorn; of glotonye,</L>
<L>Nou shole &yogh;e here of lecherye!</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis noman so wys in londe</L>
<L>&THORN;at may make to vnderstonde</L>
<L>Lewed men, what lecherie is,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei nile not leouen it ywis.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei seyen often &thorn;at men may here</L>
<L>&THORN;at sengel man and womman in fere</L>
<L>&THORN;at beo togedere and children winne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it is no dedly sinne.</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at out of wedlok is,</L>
<L>It is dedly sinne ywis,</L>
<L>Horedam and lecherie,</L>
<L>Or ellus mot holy writ lye.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne wile somme seye &thorn;us</L>
<L>And despute a&yogh;ein Iesus,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at thinke sinne suete</L>
<L>Seie &thorn;at god almyghty hete</L>
<L>&THORN;at man and womman in compaignye</L>
<L>Sholde &thorn;e world multeplie,</L>
<L>Echon wi&thorn; o&thorn;er don his kynde.</L>
<L>Bot on point &thorn;ei leue behinde,</L>
<L>And is a gret poynt ywis,</L>
<L>So&thorn;eliche wi&thorn; outen les,</L>
<L>And if &yogh;e wilen holde &yogh;oure pees,</L>
<L>On &thorn;ing &yogh;e shol witen ywis:</L>
<L>&THORN;at a kinde &thorn;ing it is, where man is lef,</L>
<L>Forto ete motoun or beof;</L>
<L>Bot on &thorn;ing &thorn;er is, be god:</L>
<L>And a man ete it vnsode,
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="190"></L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e he ete&thorn; his oune deth,</L>
<L>And godes creature he sleth.</L>
<L>Bot tak and seth it wel afyn,</L>
<L>Or in water or in wyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;an may man at his wille</L>
<L>Eten &thorn;er of al his fille.</L>
<L>And also I seye &thorn;us</L>
<L>&THORN;at oure lord suete Iesus</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his oune mouth beheet,</L>
<L>Er Adam of &thorn;e appel et,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he and Eue in companye</L>
<L>Sholde &thorn;e world multeplie,</L>
<L>Bot in spousehod he heet,</L>
<L>For him &thorn;ouhte &thorn;e ordre swet.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore as &yogh;e may here:</L>
<L>God spousede hem in fere,</L>
<L>Eueryman ensample to &yogh;iue</L>
<L>In clene lyf forto liue,</L>
<L>In spousehode out of lecherye,</L>
<L>And serue god and seint Marie.</L>
<L>For men and wymmen of hot blod</L>
<L>&THORN;enke &thorn;at lecherye is god,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nile no spousing abide,</L>
<L>Bot liuen in lecherie and pride.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore is mad shrift of mouthe</L>
<L>Est and west, north and southe.</L>
<L>And an o&thorn;ere poynt &thorn;er is:</L>
<L>When man caste&thorn; his eye amis</L>
<L>And seo&thorn; an o&thorn;er mannes wif</L>
<L>Or a womman of sengle lyf,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is of hide and of blee</L>
<L>A fairere womman &thorn;an ha&thorn; he,</L>
<L>And thenke&thorn;, I wolde &thorn;ou were myn &mdash;</L>
<L>I seye &thorn;e be seint Martyn,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at &thorn;ought if he were hent,</L>
<L>&THORN;an were &thorn;at sely soule shent,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; outen shrift and he dye,</L>
<L>Er elles mot holy writ lye.</L>
<L>Long it were forso&thorn;e to me</L>
<L>Forto telle, so mot I theo,
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="191"></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e pointes &thorn;at touche&thorn; sinne</L>
<L>Of lecherie &thorn;at touche&thorn; sinne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou haue &yogh;e herd a partye,</L>
<L>What perile come&thorn; of lecherie.</L>
<L>Nou shole &yogh;e here of coueitise,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is an o&thorn;er wise!</L>
<L>&THORN;ei man coueite londes and ledes,</L>
<L>Castels, boures and heye stedes,</L>
<L>Gold, siluer and tresour,</L>
<L>To liuen inne wi&thorn; honour</L>
<L>And forto marie wi&thorn; his childur,</L>
<L>As dide before him his eldur,</L>
<L>And of his catel wi&thorn; hem &yogh;iue</L>
<L>To helpe &thorn;e world forto liue</L>
<L>And helpe pore &thorn;at ha&thorn; neode,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e to clo&thorn;e and to feode,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei he coueite neuere so myche</L>
<L>In &thorn;is maner sikerliche</L>
<L>&THORN;at he may wi&thorn; treuthe winne &mdash;</L>
<L>Suche coueitise is no sinne.</L>
<L>Bot man &thorn;at winne&thorn; londes and ledes</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; trecherie and false dedes</L>
<L>And lei&thorn; tresour in tresorye</L>
<L>And let sely pore men die</L>
<L>And let it ligge stille &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noman &thorn;e better fare</L>
<L>Ne noman mot &thorn;er offe winne &mdash;</L>
<L>Suche coueitise so is sinne.</L>
<L>Or marchaund wi&thorn; hise marchandise<MILESTONE N="158" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To loken in alle kynne wise,</L>
<L>Hou myche he may wi&thorn;<SUP>1</SUP> treuthe winne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no trecherie is inne,</L>
<L>And in wille if he beo</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er man als wel as he</L>
<L>And of suche, as he may gete,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue&thorn; pore men cloth and mete &mdash;</L>
<L>In &thorn;is maner &thorn;ei he winne,</L>
<L>It is told for no sinne.</L>
<L>Bot who so coueite day and nyght,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e wi&thorn; wrong and wi&thorn; right,
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="192"></L>
<L>Catel winne and leye to hepe</L>
<L>And lete tresour ligge and slepe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. sleple</NOTE></L>
<L>And fare&thorn; him self wel at mele</L>
<L>And &yogh;eue&thorn; pore men litel dele,</L>
<L>And whan he shal bye or selle,</L>
<L>Is for coueitise in wille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noman sholde after him winne &mdash;</L>
<L>Suche coueitise is dedly sinne.</L>
<L>Or if a man haue for neode</L>
<L>Leid to wedde on of his wede</L>
<L>Or any of his o&thorn;er thing,</L>
<L>Pot or panne, broche or ring,</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at it ha&thorn; in wolde</L>
<L>Here&thorn; telle, it mot beo solde,</L>
<L>And he wot it wel in thought</L>
<L>And bye&thorn; it haluendel fo[r] nought &mdash;</L>
<L>A foul coueitise &thorn;at is</L>
<L>And an oker for so&thorn;e ywis.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of pride and glotonye,</L>
<L>Of coueitise and lecherie</L>
<L>Nou haue &yogh;e herd a partye,</L>
<L>Nou shole &yogh;e here of enuye!</L>
<L>Enuye is a foul sinne,</L>
<L>And myche peopul li&thorn; &thorn;er inne.</L>
<L>If a man haue enuie</L>
<L>To his neighbores hosbondrie</L>
<L>Of tilthe or of o&thorn;er thing,</L>
<L>Of triste or of housing,</L>
<L>And fonde&thorn; bo&thorn;e nyght and day</L>
<L>To make his better, if he may,</L>
<L>&THORN;an his neighbores is &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;er offe do&thorn; he not amis.</L>
<L>For whi &thorn;at he in wille beo,</L>
<L>His neighebour fare as wel as he</L>
<L>And be for him neuer &thorn;e wors</L>
<L>On his body ne in his pours,</L>
<L>God nis not wroth wi&thorn; &thorn;at enuie</L>
<L>&THORN;at turne&thorn; to no felonye.</L>
<L>Bot if he haue gret enuie
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="193"></L>
<L>To his neighebores hosbonderye</L>
<L>And wolde, his lond were vntyled</L>
<L>And his houses vnhiled,</L>
<L>For as myche as he wolde beo</L>
<L>Holden better hosebond &thorn;an he,</L>
<L>Or if he wolde for enuie</L>
<L>Seon his neighbore sone die</L>
<L>&THORN;an were in manhode arise<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So im Ms</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And better auaunced &thorn;an hise.</L>
<L>Or if he wolde for enuie</L>
<L>Putte a man out of baillie,</L>
<L>To make him worse, &thorn;an he were,</L>
<L>And putte an o&thorn;er man &thorn;ere &mdash;</L>
<L>In suche enuie who so is,</L>
<L>It is dedly sinne ywis.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou haue &yogh;e herd of enuie,</L>
<L>Of coueitise and glotonye,</L>
<L>Of pride and of lecherie &mdash;</L>
<L>Here is a foul compaignye,</L>
<L>When alle beon ybrought in fere;</L>
<L>Of angur and ire &yogh;e shol here</L>
<L>&THORN;at beo&thorn; sibbe to &thorn;ese fiue,</L>
<L>And alle beon shrewes, so mot I thriue.</L>
<L>Angur and ire &thorn;at man is inne</L>
<L>Is &thorn;e fifte dedly synne.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ei man beo of heye blod</L>
<L>And wole gladly ch&amacr;nge mod</L>
<L>And nile his neighebour bot god,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;oruh heynesse of blod,</L>
<L>And chit his meyne and his childre,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e &yogh;onger and &thorn;e eldre &mdash;</L>
<L>Suche angur and ire, as &thorn;at is,</L>
<L>Nis no dedly synne ywis.</L>
<L>Or if a man is feble of wit</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his neighbore chit,</L>
<L>Forto abate his heye mod,</L>
<L>And nile his neighbore bot god,</L>
<L>&THORN;at chyt for his feble brayn
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="194"></L>
<L>And wole beon at on ful fayn &mdash;</L>
<L>Suche angur, as &thorn;is is,</L>
<L>No dedly synne it nis.</L>
<L>Or if his neighbore in a cas</L>
<L>Haue do&ntilde; him any trespas,</L>
<L>&THORN;an he thenk nyght and day</L>
<L>To haue amendes, if he may,</L>
<L>And non o&thorn;er harm him nile,</L>
<L>Bot haue amendes be right skile,</L>
<L>And after is in gode loue &mdash;</L>
<L>Suche ire shal beo sone for&yogh;eue.</L>
<L>Bot who so is in wille pilt</L>
<L>To man &thorn;at haue&thorn; him agilt,</L>
<L>Forto slen him or to bete</L>
<L>In &thorn;at angur and &thorn;at hete,</L>
<L>Or if he dar not him selue,</L>
<L>Hyre&thorn; ten men or twelue,</L>
<L>To brek his legges or his armes</L>
<L>Or on his catel do him harmes,</L>
<L>To make him leose his worldly winne &mdash;</L>
<L>Such ire is dedly sinne;</L>
<L>Kep iche man him wel &thorn;er fro,</L>
<L>Suche ire do&thorn; &thorn;e soule wo.</L>
<L>Nou haue &yogh;e herd of lecherie,</L>
<L>Of pride and of golotonye,</L>
<L>Of coueitise and enuie</L>
<L>And of ire a partye,</L>
<L>Nou shole &yogh;e here of an o&thorn;er:</L>
<L>Nithe and onde, &thorn;at is here bro&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Many man wile ete and drinke</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; an o&thorn;er swete and swink</L>
<L>And bere him fair companye</L>
<L>And thinke&thorn; al on felonie</L>
<L>And peyne&thorn; him faire forto speke</L>
<L>And &thorn;enke&thorn; to ben awreke</L>
<L>Of trespas &thorn;at was do&ntilde; &yogh;ore,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at is &thorn;e fendes lore.</L>
<L>A mon forto turne his loue</L>
<L>For &thorn;ing &thorn;at ones is for&yogh;eue,</L>
<L>Certenly in &thorn;at cas
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="195"></L>
<L>He nis no better &thorn;an Iudas,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he was to Iesu comen,</L>
<L>He kist him and made him nomen.</L>
<L>If any man &thorn;at liue&thorn; in londe</L>
<L>Leue&thorn; in ire and in onde</L>
<L>And nile a man his gilt for&yogh;iue,</L>
<L>So may not his soule liue.</L>
<L>For holy writ shewe&thorn; &thorn;us,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ese clerkes tellen vs,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei a man go barfot euere</L>
<L>And were lynnen clothes neuere</L>
<L>And eche day faste watur and bred,</L>
<L>&THORN;at not elles c&omacr;m in his hed,</L>
<L>And made a fyr for his sinne</L>
<L>And let his body &thorn;er inne brenne &mdash;</L>
<L>In nithe and onde if he were founde,<MILESTONE N="158b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e soule eode to hell gronde;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; outen loue and charite</L>
<L>May no man saued beo.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore eche man stonde</L>
<L>And putte fro him nythe and onde;</L>
<L>In his herte if it dwelle,</L>
<L>It wile drawe him to helle,</L>
<L>Doun into &thorn;e deppest pit,</L>
<L>Er elles lye&thorn; holy writ.</L>
<L>And who so is in helle pilt</L>
<L>For his trespas and his gilt,</L>
<L>Seint Poul bere&thorn; witnes:</L>
<L>May help him no godenesse &mdash;</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; seint Poul ywis</L>
<L>No lesing founde &thorn;er is.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou haue [&yogh;e] herd of glotonie,</L>
<L>Of pride and of lecherie,</L>
<L>Of coueitise and enuie</L>
<L>And of ire a partye,</L>
<L>Of ny&thorn;e and onde, &thorn;at is here bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Nou shul &yogh;e here of an o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Of sleuthe, whiche a shrewe it is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at make&thorn; men to don amis.</L>
<L>Sleuthe is in many wise,
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="196"></L>
<L>God &yogh;eue vs grace forto rise!</L>
<L>If man is hol wi&thorn; outen h&amacr;rm</L>
<L>And li&thorn; in his bed w&amacr;rm</L>
<L>And here to &thorn;e messe ringe</L>
<L>Or knille to &thorn;e sakeringe</L>
<L>And li&thorn; stille and nile not rise &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;an he is slou&yogh; in godes seruise.</L>
<L>Or man &thorn;at al &thorn;e wike long</L>
<L>Wirke&thorn; mete and hyre to fong,</L>
<L>Bot he peyne him on sonenday,</L>
<L>Also for&thorn; as he may,</L>
<L>As erly to go to chirche,</L>
<L>As &thorn;at day he go&thorn; to wirche,</L>
<L>And thanke&thorn; him &thorn;at al ha&thorn; sent,</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e in sleuth he is hent.</L>
<L>Or if a man serue an o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>A fremde man or his brother,</L>
<L>In any maner of swink</L>
<L>For hyre, mete or for drink,</L>
<L>Beo he lewed, beo he clerk,</L>
<L>If he ou&yogh;t forsleuthe his werk,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;eue&thorn; him mete and seruise &mdash;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at sleuthe he mot arise,</L>
<L>If &thorn;at he wile treuly winne</L>
<L>Mete and hyre wi&thorn; out sinne;</L>
<L>Who so wile god queme,</L>
<L>Of such sleuthe he mot him &yogh;eme.</L>
<L>And an o&thorn;er sleuthe &thorn;er is</L>
<L>&THORN;at eile&thorn; man ywis.</L>
<L>In lentone, whan men sholde beo shriuen</L>
<L>And in clene lyf liuen,</L>
<L>&THORN;er beo&thorn; many men and fele</L>
<L>&THORN;at tenden to worldes wele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at here o&thorn;ere neodes beo do</L>
<L>And seye &thorn;at men mot tende &thorn;er to,</L>
<L>Out of sinne to beon ybound &mdash;</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e in sleuthe &thorn;ei beo founde.</L>
<L>God &thorn;at wolde fro de&thorn; arise</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue us grace fro sleu&thorn; to rise!</L>
<L>Also whan a man is shriue
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="197"></L>
<L>And thenke&thorn; in clene lif to liue,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e preost whan he is com,</L>
<L>And he ha&thorn; his penance nom</L>
<L>And let it out of his &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>And for&yogh;et and do&thorn; hit nought,</L>
<L>&THORN;e penance &thorn;at is him aioynt,</L>
<L>Wit him wel wi&thorn; &thorn;at poynt!</L>
<L>Bot he do it verrayment,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere he is in sleuthe hent.</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e it is a foul sinne</L>
<L>Any man to liuen inne!</L>
<L>&THORN;ese beo dedly sinnes seuen</L>
<L>&THORN;at letten men to com to heuen.</L>
<L>God &yogh;eue us grace &thorn;o to shone</L>
<L>&THORN;at we beon wor&thorn;i forto wo&ntilde;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e ioye &thorn;at no serwe may greue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god ha&thorn; mad to oure beheue.</L>
<L>Amen, amen, par charite,</L>
<L>If &thorn;at his blessed wille beo.</L>
<TRAILER>Expliciunt VII<SUP>tem</SUP> peccata mortalia. Incipiunt decem precepta.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV5>
<DIV5 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Incipiunt decem precepta.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;at thenke to beo shriuen</L>
<L>And out of dedly sinne to liuen,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e men and wymmen,</L>
<L>Herkene&thorn; godes hestes ten!</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;at haue &yogh;eres twelle,</L>
<L>As god comaunded him selue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ten hestes &thorn;ei sholde holde,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at were ten wintur olde,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e heye and eke lowe</L>
<L>&THORN;e ten hestes sholde knowe.</L>
<L>Vnderstond wel &thorn;is:</L>
<L>A lesse lord &thorn;an god is</L>
<L>&THORN;at comaunded his men to do</L>
<L>A thing &thorn;at his herte fel to
<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="198"></L>
<L>And behette hem auauncement</L>
<L>To holden his comaundement &mdash;</L>
<L>Which man is it &thorn;at nolde</L>
<L>Gladliche his hestes holde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; oute hous and wi&thorn; inne,</L>
<L>His auauncement to winne?</L>
<L>And non auauncement &thorn;er nis</L>
<L>A&yogh;ein &thorn;e blisse of heue&ntilde; ywis</L>
<L>&THORN;at god ha&thorn; granted alle men</L>
<L>&THORN;at holden his hestes ten.</L>
<L>Wel aughte bo&thorn;e &yogh;ong and olde</L>
<L>His comaundementz to holde!</L>
<L>Herkene&thorn; nou, &yogh;e lewede men,</L>
<L>Whiche beon &thorn;e hestes ten,</L>
<L>As it is founde in holy writ</L>
<L>Among &thorn;ese clerkes deope in wit.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e forme comaundement ywis</L>
<L>And &thorn;e hyest, &thorn;at is &thorn;is.</L>
<L>We shole honoure ouer alle thing</L>
<L>Suete Iesu, heuene king,</L>
<L>Eche morw, whan we rise,</L>
<L>Begynne first in his seruise.</L>
<L>For beo he lewed man or clerk</L>
<L>&THORN;at begynne&thorn; any werk,</L>
<L>Er he serue &thorn;e king of myght,</L>
<L>He halt not &thorn;at heste aryght.</L>
<L>For who so gynne any thing,</L>
<L>Er he serue oure heuen king,</L>
<L>What man euere it beo ywis,</L>
<L>A gret tokenyng it is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he loue&thorn; &thorn;at werk more,</L>
<L>&THORN;an he do&thorn; godes lore.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore eche man &thorn;at may</L>
<L>Serue god formest a day,</L>
<L>Er he do any o&thorn;er thing,</L>
<L>&THORN;is is oure forme begynnyng.</L>
<L>Of godes hestes hered mot he wor&thorn;e<MILESTONE N="159" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he lette us here in eor&thorn;e!</L>
<L>Oure euen cristen we shold loue,</L>
<L>As god hette &thorn;at sit aboue.
<PB REF="00000207.tif" N="199"></L>
<L>God nile not &thorn;at we &yogh;eue</L>
<L>&THORN;at we sholde oure self bi liue;</L>
<L>Bot if we may ought spare</L>
<L>And oure self wel fare,</L>
<L>God wile &thorn;at we &yogh;iue</L>
<L>To helpe oure euene criste&ntilde; to liue.</L>
<L>And if we may &yogh;eue hem nought,</L>
<L>Wilne we hem goed in oure thought;</L>
<L>And bot wee doon verrayment,</L>
<L>We breke godes comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er comaundement is &thorn;is</L>
<L>&THORN;at god, &thorn;at almyghty is,</L>
<L>King of heuen &thorn;at al do may,</L>
<L>Comanded vs holde oure haliday,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e lewede men and clerkes,</L>
<L>And not only of eor&thorn;ly werkes,</L>
<L>Bot holde vs out of dedly sinne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we falle not &thorn;er inne,</L>
<L>And helpe &thorn;e pore wi&thorn; al oure myght &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;an holde we oure haliday right.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sholde echeman on liue</L>
<L>On haliday kepe his wittes fiue,</L>
<L>Forto mende dede and thought,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e wike is yuele wrought.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e thridde comaundement ywis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god comaunded, so is &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at echeman be his myght</L>
<L>Honoure fader and moder aright.</L>
<L>Wel aughte eche man in eor&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Were &thorn;ei neuere so litel wor&thorn;e,</L>
<L>To honoure fader and moder here,</L>
<L>And resoun were, as &yogh;e may here.</L>
<L>Suete Iesu, ful of myght,</L>
<L>Cam into er&thorn;e fro heuene light</L>
<L>And fette hise into heuene;</L>
<L>Blessede beo his names seue&ntilde;</L>
<L>&THORN;at com his moder to honoure,</L>
<L>Wel aughte we to menske oure!</L>
<L>And who so wile not beo war</L>
<L>To honoure &thorn;e moder &thorn;at him bar
<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="200"></L>
<L>And &thorn;e fader &thorn;at him gat,</L>
<L>Beo him wel war of &thorn;at:</L>
<L>Bot he helpe hem at nede,</L>
<L>Shert lyf shal ben his mede</L>
<L>And lu&thorn;er ending ywis,</L>
<L>Or holy writ speke&thorn; amis.</L>
<L>And who so honoure&thorn; aright</L>
<L>Fader and moder be al his myght,</L>
<L>He shal haue atte gynnyng</L>
<L>Long lyf and goed endyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou shole &yogh;e here of &thorn;e ferthe</L>
<L>&THORN;at god ha&thorn; comanded in er&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in ernest and in game</L>
<L>In ydel nempne not his name.</L>
<L>If a man sek or wroth</L>
<L>Swere&thorn; any gret oth</L>
<L>And nempne&thorn; godes name &thorn;er inne,</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e &thorn;ere he do&thorn; dedly sinne.</L>
<L>Whan he any oth swere&thorn;,</L>
<L>Godes limes he totere&thorn;,</L>
<L>Or in gamen or in chest,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he breke&thorn; godes hest,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nempne&thorn; his name in any stede,</L>
<L>Bot it beo in holy bede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fifte comaundement is &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at holy writ telle&thorn; vs:</L>
<L>After man ha&thorn; wit nomen</L>
<L>And is out of fonston comen,</L>
<L>Shal lete misbeleue gon</L>
<L>And leoue in no god bot on.</L>
<L>Who so leoue&thorn; on fals sermoun</L>
<L>O&thorn;er on coniuresoun,</L>
<L>He is out of right beleoue</L>
<L>And is about god to greoue.</L>
<L>Suche beleoue were goed laft,</L>
<L>It is not bot &thorn;e deoueles craft.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN; e sixte comaundement of tene</L>
<L>Of godes sone wi&thorn; out wene:</L>
<L>Vpon bok swere no fals oth,</L>
<L>No&thorn;er for leof ne for loth!
<PB REF="00000209.tif" N="201"></L>
<L>First whan he wile begynne</L>
<L>To swere fals for worldes winne,</L>
<L>He forsake&thorn; his cristendam,</L>
<L>Atte fonston &thorn;at he nam,</L>
<L>And bind him in an o&thorn;er bond,</L>
<L>On bok whan he lei&thorn; his hond;</L>
<L>Beo he lewed, beo he clerk,</L>
<L>He forsake&thorn; al &thorn;e werk,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e werkes of godenesse</L>
<L>&THORN;at euere he dide more and lesse,</L>
<L>In al his liue &thorn;at he ha&thorn; wrought,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at oth if he ought.</L>
<L>And whan he kissed &thorn;e bok,</L>
<L>His gode dedes all he forsok;</L>
<L>He forsake&thorn; his godes bedes</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ha&thorn; seid in gode stedes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ha&thorn; beden al his lyf,</L>
<L>Sithe &thorn;at he was boren of wif.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e seuene&thorn; hest &thorn;at god het,</L>
<L>In paradys &thorn;o he Adam let,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for mede ne for destresse</L>
<L>No man bere fals wittenesse</L>
<L>Of thing &thorn;at falsnesse is inne,</L>
<L>For no mede ne for no winne.</L>
<L>Of falsnes come&thorn; myche wo,</L>
<L>Wite eche man wel him &thorn;er fro!</L>
<L>Bere no fals witnes in lond</L>
<L>A&yogh;ein him &thorn;at ha&thorn; right on honde!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN; e eighte&thorn; hest, as &yogh;e shal here:</L>
<L>&THORN;at god &thorn;at bought vs alle deore</L>
<L>Comaunde&thorn; alle &thorn;at beon him leof,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man shal be no theof;</L>
<L>For who so is nomen &thorn;er inne,</L>
<L>Theofte is a foul sinne.</L>
<L>Man &thorn;at ha&thorn; not &thorn;at him is leof</L>
<L>And &thorn;er fore become&thorn; a theof</L>
<L>And stele&thorn; trewe mennes goed,</L>
<L>To meyntenc his hie blod &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;ese fendes mette,</L>
<L>Thefte and coueitise togedere sette.
<PB REF="00000210.tif" N="202"></L>
<L>An o&thorn;er sinne beginne&thorn; to wake,</L>
<L>Whan mannes catel do&thorn; aslake</L>
<L>And stele&thorn; goed his pouert to hide,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he is fallen in pride.</L>
<L>Or if it is a pore man</L>
<L>&THORN;at no mester ne can,</L>
<L>Or is feble and may not swinke</L>
<L>To winne him no&thorn;er mete ne drinke,</L>
<L>Or is not strong mon to gete</L>
<L>And wonde&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. wonde&thorn; <I>deutl</I>.</NOTE> for pride to gete his mete</L>
<L>And liue&thorn; wi&thorn; theft and mycherie &mdash;</L>
<L>Pride is in his companye,</L>
<L>&THORN;oruh &thorn;e fendes quointyse.</L>
<L>Nou is theft and coueitise</L>
<L>And pride, &thorn;e thre, mette infere,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e fer&thorn;e nou shol &yogh;e here.</L>
<L>If a man haue not mete ryf,</L>
<L>Bot simpeliche to holde his lyf,</L>
<L>And is pilt in a wille</L>
<L>To stele his body forto fille,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he falle&thorn; in glotonie.</L>
<L>Nou beon foure in companye:</L>
<L>Theofte, coueitise, pride &thorn;erto<MILESTONE N="159b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And glotonie, a shrewe also.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fifte shrewe &thorn;er is it</L>
<L>And ful neigh his felawe sit.</L>
<L>A man &thorn;at may swete and swinke</L>
<L>And winne clothes, mete and drinke</L>
<L>And stele&thorn; to liue in esy lif,</L>
<L>Be it man, mayde or wif,</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e in sleuthe he is founde</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e fifte sinne ybounde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;et &thorn;er is &thorn;e sixte shrewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;er of taken &yogh;eme ful fewe.</L>
<L>Whan a man become&thorn; a theof,</L>
<L>He do&thorn; god an o&thorn;er gref.</L>
<L>He suppose&thorn;: &thorn;e feond is</L>
<L>More of poer, &thorn;an god is,
<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="203"></L>
<L>Forto take to him hede</L>
<L>To fynde him &thorn;at he ha&thorn; neode,</L>
<L>And in his hert he is adrad</L>
<L>&THORN;at god &thorn;at on &thorn;e Rode was sprad</L>
<L>Nile him not eche day &yogh;iue</L>
<L>&THORN;at he myht bi liue.</L>
<L>&THORN;er he is in wanhope falle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e worste sinne of alle.</L>
<L>In wanhope who so is nome,</L>
<L>He shal neuere in heue&ntilde; come.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e nithe comaundement &thorn;er is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man &thorn;at cristened is</L>
<L>Shal wi&thorn; tong ne wi&thorn; honde</L>
<L>Sle no man in no londe.</L>
<L>A man may, as &yogh;e may here,</L>
<L>Slen a man in two manere:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mannes honde is &thorn;at on,</L>
<L>So is slayn manyon;</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; tong &thorn;at o&thorn;er is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is worse &thorn;an &thorn;at ywis.</L>
<L>If a man procure&thorn; an o&thorn;er ought</L>
<L>And is in wille thought</L>
<L>&THORN;at he leose his honour</L>
<L>Or his worldes tresour,</L>
<L>In al &thorn;at in him is,</L>
<L>He sle&thorn; him in &thorn;at wille ywis.</L>
<L>And in a quest if he beo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a man shal dampned beo</L>
<L>Falseliche wi&thorn; oute gilt,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at quest who so is pilt,</L>
<L>And he take &thorn;er offe hede</L>
<L>&THORN;at man wile dampne him for mede</L>
<L>And he beo at &thorn;at assent</L>
<L>At &thorn;e day of Iugement,</L>
<L>&THORN;at point shal on him beo pilt</L>
<L>Of his deth to bere &thorn;e gilt.</L>
<L>An o&thorn;er maner slauht &thorn;er is:</L>
<L>If a pore man fare&thorn; amis</L>
<L>For hongur or for misese</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou myht him ought ese
<PB REF="00000212.tif" N="204"></L>
<L>And holde &thorn;i lyf and his,</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou suffre him fare amis,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at point and &thorn;ou dye</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou it wi&thorn; &thorn;in eye<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sinn? Entstellt!</I></NOTE> &mdash;</L>
<L>Be &thorn;e hed &thorn;at I bere,</L>
<L>Of his deth &thorn;ou shalt answere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e laste comaundement of ten</L>
<L>&THORN;at god comaunded alle men:</L>
<L>Coueite non o&thorn;er mannes wif</L>
<L>Forto apeire here bei&thorn;er lif.</L>
<L>Coueite not his wif alone</L>
<L>Ne his o&thorn;ere godes none</L>
<L>Ne no wif, o&thorn;eres spouse,</L>
<L>Ne no goed &thorn;at falle&thorn; to house.</L>
<L>Nou haue &yogh;e herd, wymmen and men,</L>
<L>God almyhties hestes ten.</L>
<L>I haue told &yogh;ou no falsnesse,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at &thorn;e bok bere&thorn; witnesse.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;er nis nou&thorn;er &yogh;ong ne old</L>
<L>&THORN;at of articles &thorn;at I haue told</L>
<L>&THORN;at may wite him wi&thorn; hem alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne shal in somme falle.</L>
<L>We beo so feble sikerliche,</L>
<L>We mote sinnen nedeliche.</L>
<L>Bot godes mercy is so myche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &thorn;ei we sinne dedliche,</L>
<L>Est and west, nor&thorn; and souht,</L>
<L>God ha&thorn; ordeined shrift of mou&thorn;.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei man falle, he shal arise</L>
<L>And turne a&yogh;ein to his seruise.</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis man so holy non</L>
<L>Mad of flessh and of bon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at so wel loke him may,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne falle&thorn; seuen si&thorn;e a day.</L>
<L>God lene vs sone rise</L>
<L>And ende in his suete seruise. Amen.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV5>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="manuscript source"><PB REF="00000213.tif" N="205">
<HEAD>B. Ms. Harl. 1706 (Papier, 15. saec.).</HEAD>
<DIV5 TYPE="editorial note">
<P>Auf die Zehn Gebote und Sieben Tods&uuml;nden folgen noch: Septem virtutes, 7 opera charitatis etc. etc.; zuletzt 4 virtutes cardinales, 8 beatitudines. Die Decem Mandata finden sich in gleicher Fassung auch in Ms. Harl. 5396.</P></DIV5>
<DIV5 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Decem Mandata.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thou schalte haue on god and no moo</L>
<L>And ouer alle &thorn;inge loue him also.</L>
<L>Goddys name in ydel take &thorn;ou nou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Ne swere by no&thorn;inge &thorn;at god ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Haue mynde to halowe &thorn;i holyday</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;i mayn, man and maye.</L>
<L>&THORN;i fa&thorn;er and modyr worschipe bo&thorn;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; counselle, comforte, meete and cloo&thorn;.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt not slee lowde ne stylle</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; tonge ne knyfe ne wycked wylle.</L>
<L>Lechery schalt &thorn;ou noon doo</L>
<L>In wylle ne worde ne dede also.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt not stele &thorn;i ney&yogh;bores &thorn;inge,</L>
<L>By gyle ne raueyn ne wronge wi&thorn;holdynge.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalte not speke no false wytnessynge,</L>
<L>In worde ne dede make no lesynge.</L>
<L>&THORN;i ney&yogh;bores &thorn;inge coueyte &thorn;ou noon,</L>
<L>Ne vnmeuable &thorn;inge, feld ne towne.</L>
<L>&THORN;i ney&yogh;bores wyfe desyre &thorn;ou nou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Seruant ne mayden ne o&thorn;er au&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;ese ben &thorn;e hestes tenne</L>
<L>&THORN;at god comaunde&thorn; to alle men.</L>
</LG>
</DIV5>
<DIV5 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Sieben Tods&uuml;nden.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Pryde ys hede of alle kynne synne</L>
<L>&THORN;at make&thorn; mannes soule fro god to twyne.</L>
<L>To wicked hy&yogh;nes he wolde ay</L>
<L>And loue&thorn; to myche ys owne noblye;</L>
<L>Hym self he preyse&thorn; in hys &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er men he sette&thorn; at nou&yogh;te.
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="206"></L>
<L>Enuye folowe&THORN; pryde comenlye.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Inuidia</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan men faren welle, he is sorye;</L>
<L>Whan men faren yuel, he ioye&thorn; wi&thorn; ynne;</L>
<L>He lawe&thorn; neu[e]r, but at synne.</L>
<L>Wra&thorn;e vn to &thorn;ise two ys knytte;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ira</NOTE></L>
<L>To take vengeaunce ys alle hys wytte,</L>
<L>To slee, to smy&yogh;te, to procure woo,</L>
<L>To wary folke, to sclaunder also.</L>
<L>The couetouse man knowe&thorn; no skylle,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Auaricia</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;is world maye not hym fylle;</L>
<L>The worldes wel&thorn;e he wylle&thorn; ay</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ry&yogh;te or wronge gete, whe&thorn;er he may.</L>
<L>Glotenye ha&thorn; grete appetyte<NOTE PLACE="marg">Gula</NOTE></L>
<L>To eete erly and late hys dely&yogh;te.</L>
<L>He loue&thorn; no mesure of etynge,</L>
<L>And aye he wold be drynkynge.</L>
<L>The sixte synne ys lecherye,<MILESTONE N="306" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">Luxuria</NOTE></L>
<L>To many a soule yt worche&thorn; noye.</L>
<L>But men yt leue and hem amende,</L>
<L>In fyre of helle &thorn;[e]i schulle be breende.</L>
<L>Slownesse ys a cursed &thorn;inge,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Accidia</NOTE></L>
<L>For yt ys ay wery of wylle doynge.</L>
<L>Good werke hym lo&thorn;e&thorn; to bygynne,</L>
<L>And lytyl &thorn;ere of wolle he blynne.</L>
<L>&THORN;ese ben &thorn;e synnes seuene</L>
<L>&THORN;at reuen a man &thorn;e blysse of heuene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV5>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="manuscript source">
<HEAD>C. Ms. Arundel 20 (Papier, 15. saec.).</HEAD>
<DIV5 TYPE="editorial note">
<P>Die Zehn Gebote finden sich auf fol. 43-56 b, die Sieben Tods&uuml;nden von fol. 57-70 b; beides sind lang ausgef&uuml;hrte und mit Narrationes durchsetzte Traktate. Als Probe m&ouml;ge die erste Strophe von beiden gen&uuml;gen.</P></DIV5>
<DIV5 TYPE="poem">
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>The fyrst commandment off all &thorn;e lawe</L>
<L>Ys: &thorn;ou xalt haue no mo goddes but on,</L>
<L>Hym only to worshypp, loue and awe</L>
<L>With hart and thou&yogh;t, as sure as stone,</L>
<L>The maker off man &mdash; other god ys &thorn;er non &mdash;</L>
<L>In whom 3 persones be closyd and knytt,</L>
<L>Gyffyng to man all wysdom and wytt.
<PB REF="00000215.tif" N="207"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sacrylege in Englyssh ys, as I can conceyff,</L>
<L>A thyng &thorn;at a man fro &thorn;e chyrch withholde,</L>
<L>Or with ou&yogh;t licens any thyng fro &thorn;em veyff,</L>
<L>Be yt any jewell or syluer or off golde,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;e lest thyng, &thorn;at can be thou&yogh;t or tolde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys with In &thorn;e holy chyrches pryvylage &mdash;</L>
<L>All such thyng ys callyd sacrylege.</L>
</LG>
</DIV5>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="manuscript source">
<HEAD>D. Ms. Laud 416 (Papier, 15. saec.).</HEAD>
<DIV5 TYPE="editorial note">
<P>Hierunter eine Probe der Sieben Tods&uuml;nden; f&uuml;r die Zehn Gebote vgl. Rel. Ant. II, 27.</P></DIV5>
<DIV5 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Here begynnyth a tretyce of the VII dedly synnys.<MILESTONE N="35" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of the VII dedly synnys now will I telle.</L>
<L>The maister of hem and gouernaunce is callid pride,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Superbia.</NOTE></L>
<L>Which is cheif rewler and prynce of hell.</L>
<L>Fro the blisse of hevyn he was made doune slide,</L>
<L>And in the lowyst place he is in er(th)e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms.?, undeutlich!</I></NOTE> to abide,</L>
<L>For euer mor wyth pardon and redempcioun</L>
<L>For his grete pride and high presumpcioun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L>His purpose was to haue gouernid all hevyn,</L>
<L>To be cheif hym self and haue &thorn;e dominacioun,</L>
<L>And to sytte above all the sprytes VII.</L>
<L>Thus this Lucyfer by fals vsurp[a]cioun</L>
<L>Wold haue be lyke to hym that ys lord of eueri nacioun,</L>
<L>Wherfor he was cast downe and made lowest of all,</L>
<L>Becawse he wold to his souerayne in estate be egall.</L>
</LG>
</DIV5>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="poems">
<HEAD>II. Christ on the cross.</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="manuscript source">
<HEAD>A. Ms. New Coll. Oxford LXXXVIII. (Pergament, Anfang des XIV. Jh.)</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Dieses in einen lat. Text eingeschobene St&uuml;ck, das ich erst im letzten Augenblicke gefunden habe, steht dem 1. Teile der Kildare-Version sehr nahe und beweist, da&szlig; derartige Gedichte um 1300 g&auml;ng und g&auml;be waren. Die Ankl&auml;nge sind 
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="208"> z. T. w&ouml;rtlich (cf. <I>Turn mi bodi abuten, oueral &thorn;u findest blod</I>), der hier zu Grunde liegende lat. Text (nach Augustinus) ist fast derselbe wie in der Kildare-Verson, ja er entspricht der englischen &Uuml;bertragung wenigstens bei den Schlu&szlig;worten viel genauer als dort. Die Hs. w&uuml;rde nach dem Katalog etwa gleichzeitig sein, der englische Text ist aber viel altert&uuml;mlicher als in der Kildare-Version, wie das Relativf&uuml;rwort <I>&thorn;e</I> beweist. Hier wie dort finden sich Reimpaare, doch ist der Vers noch unregelm&auml;&szlig;iger gebaut als in der Kildare-Version und nicht geeignet uns &uuml;ber diesen gr&ouml;&szlig;ere Klarheit zu verschaffen; die Alliteration ist nur ganz schwach ausgepr&auml;gt. Da&szlig; der 1. Teil der Kildare-Version eine originale Dichtung darstellt, ist nunmehr ausgeschlossen; auch der lat. Text dieses Teiles mu&szlig; eine viel|benutzte Stelle aus Augustin gewesen sein, w&auml;hrend die &uuml;brigen lat. S&auml;tze die weitere Ausf&uuml;hrung des Dichters darstellen m&ouml;gen.</P><P>Respice in faciem Christi tui et uidebis eum dorso flagellato,<MILESTONE N="179" UNIT="folio"> latere sauciato, capite puncto uepribus, manibus perforatis, pedibus confossis; uolue et reuolue illud dominicum corpus a latere usque ad latus, a summo usque deorsum, ubique inuenies dolorem que vndique terrorem.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Man and wyman, loket to me,</L>
<L>U muchel pine ich &thorn;olede for &thorn;e!</L>
<L>Loke up one mi rig, u sore ich was ibiten,</L>
<L>Loke to mi side, wat blod ich haue ileten!</L>
<L>Mine uet an mine honden nailed beth to &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e &thorn;ornes prikiing mine hiued urnth ablode.</L>
<L>Fram side to side, fro hiued to &thorn;e fot,</L>
<L>Turn mi bodi abuten, oueral &thorn;u findest blod.</L>
<L>Man, &thorn;in hurte, &thorn;in hurte &thorn;u turne to me,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e vif wndes, &thorn;e ich tholede for &thorn;e!</L>
</LG>
<P>Auf der folgenden Seite (fol. 179b) stehen noch folgende englische Verse:</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Louerd, &thorn;u clepedest me,</L>
<L>An ich na&yogh;t ne ansuarede &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Bute wordes scloe and sclepie</L>
<L>"&THORN;ole, &thorn;et<NOTE PLACE="foot">= &yogh;et</NOTE> &thorn;ole a litel", bute "&thorn;iet<NOTE PLACE="foot">= &yogh;iet</NOTE> and &thorn;iet" was endelis,</L>
<L>And "&thorn;ole a litel" a long wexis.
<PB REF="00000217.tif" N="209"></L>
</LG>
<P>Vgl. f&uuml;r die letzten schwer verst&auml;ndlichen Zeilen den dar&uuml;ber stehenden lat. Text:<NOTE PLACE="end">....nisi uerba lenta et sompnolenta modo ecce modo siue paululum, sed modo et modo non habebant modum, et inde<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. In</NOTE> paululum in longum ibat.</NOTE></P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="manuscript source">
<HEAD>B. Ms. Bodl. 42 und Eccl. Dun. A III 12.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE>Dasselbe geht hervor aus den beiden folgenden anfangs von mir &uuml;bersehenen Gedichten, welche auf demselben lat. Texte beruhen. Cf. Furnivall, E.E.T.S. 15 p. 214 (neue Auflage p. 243): Part of a Meditation of St. Augustine. Ich gebe das St&uuml;ck des Durham-Ms. nach Furnivall, das der Hs. Bodl. 42 nach dem Original, zumal dieses von Furnivall nur zur H&auml;lfte abgedruckt ist.</HEADNOTE>
<DIV5 TYPE="manuscript">
<HEAD>Ms. Bodl. 42, fol. 250.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wit was his nakede brest and red of blod his side,</L>
<L>Blod[i] was his faire neb, his wnden depe an uide,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. rude?</NOTE></L>
<L>Starke waren his armes, hispred op on &thorn;e rode;</L>
<L>In fif steden an<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Fur</I>. in</NOTE> his bodi stremes hurne of blode.</L>
</LG>
<P>Das Folgende fehlt bei Furnivall.</P>
<P>Respice in faciem Christi et uidebis dorso flagellato, latere sauciato, capite puncto uepribus, manibus perforatis, pedibus confossis, volue et reuolue illud dominicum corpus a latere usque ad latus, a summo usque deorsum et circumquamque inuenies dolorem et cruorem; et hoc potest anglice sic exponi.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Loke, man, to Iesucrist, hineiled an &thorn;o rode,</L>
<L>And hipicz(!) his nakede bodi, red himaked mid blode;</L>
<L>His reg mid scurge isuunge, his heued &thorn;ornes prikede,</L>
<L>&THORN;o nailes in him stikede.</L>
<L>&THORN;uend and trend &thorn;i lordes bodi, &thorn;urch wam &thorn;u art iboruhe,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;u mit hi-uinde blode an sorue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV5>
<DIV5 TYPE="manuscript">
<HEAD>Ms. Eccl. Dun. A III 12.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wyth was his halude brest and red of blod his syde,</L>
<L>Bleye was his fair handled,<NOTE PLACE="foot">= andwlit</NOTE> his wund<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lies</I> wnd</NOTE> dop ant wide,</L>
<L>And his arms ystreith hey up-hon &thorn;e rode;</L>
<L>On fif studes on his body &thorn;e stremes ran o blode.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV5>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="manuscript source"><PB REF="00000218.tif" N="210">
<HEAD>C. Ms. Arundel 507.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE>14. Jahrhundert; zusammengew&uuml;rfelte Handschrift von Papier und Pergament. Inhalt lat. und afrz., nur wenige engl. Verse hier und da eingesprengt.</HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Synful man, loke vp and see,<MILESTONE N="10" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>How reufulli I hyng on rode,</L>
<L>And of my penaunce haue pitee</L>
<L>With sorughful herte and drery mode.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;is, man, I sufferd for &thorn;e,</L>
<L>My flesh bee ryuen, forbled my blode.</L>
<L>Lift vp &thorn;i herte, &thorn;ou calle on me,</L>
<L>Forsake &thorn;i synne, haue mercy gode!</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="manuscript source">
<HEAD>D. Ms. Add. 31042 (Br. Mus.)</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Pergamenths. des 15. Jhs.</P><P>Das lange Gedicht enth&auml;lt 15 Strophen, von denen hier die beiden ersten als Probe gegeben werden.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Man, to refourme thyn exile and thi losse<MILESTONE N="94b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Frome paradyse, place of moste plesance,</L>
<L>The to restore I hange appone this crosse</L>
<L>Corouned with the thorne, woundede with the launce</L>
<L>Handes and feete to encrese my greuance,</L>
<L>With scharpe nayles my blode made ryne doune &mdash;</L>
<L>When euer thou felis any perturbance,</L>
<L>Looke one my woundes, thynke one my passioun!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thynke and remembre apon my blody fface,</L>
<L>The reede, the sponge, aysele mengyde with galle,</L>
<L>Full fele rebukes, O man, for thi trispace,</L>
<L>With hatefull spittynge &thorn;at one my vesage dide falle.</L>
<L>Kyng of Iewes in sc&omacr;rne &thorn;ay dide me calle,</L>
<L>Blyndfelde, bobbyde by false derysioun &mdash;</L>
<L>O man, for thi comforthe, amonge thi troubles alle,</L>
<L>Looke one my woundes, thynke one my passioun!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000219.tif" N="211">
<HEAD>III. Lullay.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Ms. Harl. 7358.</P><P>Nach dem Katalog "Codex chartaceus, saeculi forte decimi tertii". Der Sprache und dem &Auml;u&szlig;eren nach zu urteilen ist die Hs. eher in das 14. Jahrhundert zu setzen. Form, Inhalt und Zusammenhang des Gedichtes machen Schwierigkeiten.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lollay, lollay, &thorn;u lytel chyld,</L>
<L>Wy wepys &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP>, <I>so stets ausser 1, 1; daher auch</I> &thorn;ou <I>in die Anf&auml;nge ein|gesetzt</I>.</NOTE> so sore?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;at were so sterne and wyld,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art bycome meck<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>so im Ms</I>.</NOTE> and myld,</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; &thorn;e, Marye, &thorn;at wente wi&thorn; chyld</L>
<L>To sauy &thorn;at was forlore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lollay, lollay, &thorn;ou lytel chyld,</L>
<L>Wy wepys &thorn;ou so sore?</L>
<L>Ych wot ywys, for &thorn;er hyt ys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god ys sone suffred &thorn;is.</L>
<L>Mercy, lord, y haue do mys!</L>
<L>Ywys, ich nel no more.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lollay, lollay, &thorn;ou lytel chyld,</L>
<L>Wy wepys &thorn;ou so sore?</L>
<L>Ich tock<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>so im Ms</I>.</NOTE> anappel of &thorn;at tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at my fader forbyd hyt me,</L>
<L>Warfore ydampned schal y be,</L>
<L>Yff my wepyng nere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lollay, lollay, &thorn;ou lytel chyld,</L>
<L>Wy wepys &thorn;ou so sore?</L>
<L>An appel wyt a rewfoul res</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens my fader wylle y ches</L>
<L>Werfore myn hertage y lys,</L>
<L>For al my wepyng so sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lollay, lollay, &thorn;ou lytel chyld,</L>
<L>Wy wepys &thorn;ou so sore?
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="212"></L>
<L>Lollay for wo, &thorn;ou lytyl &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou lytel barun, &thorn;ou lytel kyng,</L>
<L>Mankynde ys cause of &thorn;y wepyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;at hast ylyued so &yogh;ore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lollay, lollay, &thorn;ou lytel chyld,</L>
<L>Wy wepys &thorn;ou so sore?</L>
<L>&YOGH;et &thorn;ou schalt suffry paynys mo</L>
<L>In herte, in fot, in hondes to &mdash;</L>
<L>Ich wot ywys &thorn;at ys al so,</L>
<L>To sauy &thorn;at were forlore.<NOTE PLACE="end">Im Ms. steht hinter Strophe 1, 2, 3, 5 eine Klammer und <I>L</I> oder <I>LL</I>, wodurch anscheinend die Worte <I>Lollay, Lollay, &thorn;ou litel chyld . . . . sore</I> zum Refrain gemacht werden; hinter Str. 4 und 6 fehlt die Klammer, wohl weil sie aus Platzmangel hintereinander geschrieben sind. Ich habe mir erlaubt, die Worte Lollay etc. nicht als Refrain zu geben, sondern an den Anfang der Strophe zu stellen, wie es in Str. 1 im Ms. der Fall ist und wie es der Reim und Bau der Strophe zu verlangen scheinen. Ich nehme an, da&szlig; ein Abschreiber die Anf&auml;nge der Strophen f&auml;lschlich als Refrain zum Vorhergehenden geh&ouml;rig auffa&szlig;te und dann Klammern und Abk&uuml;rzungen gebrauchte, wie es f&uuml;r Refrains &uuml;blich war. &mdash;</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>IV. Earth.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Ms. Cambr. Univ. Libr. Ii IV 9. Papierhandschrift des 15. Jhs.</P><P>Diese Version fiel mir leider erst sehr sp&auml;t in die H&auml;nde. Vor allen anderen Hss. der j&uuml;ngeren Version zeichnet sie sich dadurch aus, dafs sie w&ouml;rtliche Ankl&auml;nge an die Kildare-Version enth&auml;lt und damit einen weiteren und sicheren Beweis f&uuml;r direkten Zusammenhang liefert. Dahin geh&ouml;ren Stellen wie:</P><P>7, 4. <I>&thorn;e rof of his hows xal ly on his chyn</I> (Kild. 2, 6).</P><P>13, 1-4 zeigt starke Ankl&auml;nge an Kild. 2, 1-4 und hat fast die gleichen Reimw&ouml;rter.
<PB REF="00000221.tif" N="213"></P><P>20, 1-2 . . . .<I>blayke is his bours</I> (Kild. 6, 4-5).</P><P>6, 1-2 cf. <I>weye: . . . . palfreye</I> scheint aus Kild. 5, 1-2 entstellt zu sein, vielleicht auch 5, 1-4 aus Kild. Str. 1.</P><P>&Uuml;brigens ist die Version schlecht &uuml;berliefert und viele Strophen sind unvollst&auml;ndig. &mdash;</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Erthe vpon erth is waxin and wrought,<MILESTONE N="67" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Erthe takys on erth a nobylay of nought;</L>
<L>Now erthe vpon erthe layes all his &thorn;ought,</L>
<L>How erthe vpon erthe settys<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. sattys</NOTE> all at noght.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Erthe vpon erth has hallys and towres,</L>
<L>Erthe says to erth: this is alle owres;</L>
<L>But quan erth vpon erth has byggyd his bowres,</L>
<L>Than xal erth for the erth haue scharpe schowres.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Erthe vpon erth wolde be a kyng,</L>
<L>But how erth xal to erth, thynkyth he no thyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And of the same erthe mad god man,</L>
<L>And sethe he made that erth and callyd it Adam,</L>
<L>For loue of erthe, the wych was woman,</L>
<L>That erth in this erthe fyrst began.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Erthe goos on erth and tyllys with hys plowe,</L>
<L>Erthe ageyn erth holdys it full toght,</L>
<L>Erthe vpon [erth] stelis hym a flogh,</L>
<L>Erthe on this erth thynkys, he has neuer jnowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Erth vpon erthe gos in the weye,</L>
<L>Prykys and prankys on a palfreye.</L>
<L>When erth has gotyn erth alle that he maye,</L>
<L>He schal haue but seven fote at his last daye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Than xal not be lykyng vnto hym,</L>
<L>Bu(t)<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. Bu (t <I>radiert oder weggewischt</I>).</NOTE> an olde sely cloth to wynde erthe jn.</L>
<L>When erthe is in erth for wormys wyn,</L>
<L>The rof of his hows xal ly on his chyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<L>When erthe says to erth: my rent &thorn;ou me bryng,<MILESTONE N="67b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Then has erth fro erthe a dolfull partyng.
<PB REF="00000222.tif" N="214"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<L>How erthe louys erth, wondyr me thynke,</L>
<L>How erth for erth wyll swete and swynke.</L>
<L>When erth is in erthe broght with in the brynke,</L>
<L>What as herth than of erth but a fowle stynke?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Erthe wrotys in erth as molys don in molde,</L>
<L>Erth vpon erth glydys as golde,</L>
<L>As erth leve in erthe euer more schulde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Erthe vpon erth, mynd euer more &thorn;ou make</L>
<L>How erthe xal to erth, when deth wyll hym take.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Be ware, erth, for erthe for sake of thi sowle;</L>
<L>Erthe may of erth at &thorn;e last take a fowle,</L>
<L>When erthe is in erthe here so long in his slogh.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For erth gos in erth walkand in vede,</L>
<L>And erthe rydys on erth on a fayr stede;</L>
<L>When he was<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lies</I> has</NOTE> gotyn in erth erth to his mede,</L>
<L>Than is erth layde in erthe wormys to fede.</L>
<L>Whylke ar the wormys the flesch brede?</L>
<L>Gode wote the wormys for to ryght rede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Erthe ageyn erthe I holde it onkynde,</L>
<L>Erthe is as sone wroth as is the wynde,</L>
<L>Swyche fowle erth mekyl may we fynde,</L>
<L>That wyl speke fayre before vs and falsly behynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<L>When erth vpon erth begynnys to be wroth,</L>
<L>Erth vpon erth swerys many a gret othe,</L>
<L>Erth berys pride in herte and in cloth;</L>
<L>When erth is layde in erth, &thorn;an xal it be loth.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Erthly coveytous makyth erth to be schent,</L>
<L>Erth for this erth yeldes a gret rent.</L>
<L>If erth in thys erth levyd in good entent,</L>
<L>Than dare erth nevyr recke, where that he went.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Erth vpon erth is stronge as a mast,</L>
<L>And erth wyth is erth fyghtys ful fast;</L>
<L>There is non so stowte that in erth may hym cast,</L>
<L>And alle xal we be erth at the last.
<PB REF="00000223.tif" N="215"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Erthe bygyth hallys and erth bygith towres;</L>
<L>When erth is layd in erth, blayke is his bours;</L>
<L>If erth haue welth, he dwellyth in flowres;</L>
<L>And if erth haue mysdon, he getyth scharpe shours.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<L>If erth wyste in erth, quat that erth is,</L>
<L>Ther wolde neuer erth in erth do amys.</L>
<L>God mad erth of erth and namyd it for his,</L>
<L>Adam of erth in erthly paradys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<L>God walkyd in erth, as longe as he wolde.</L>
<L>He had not in this erth but honger and colde,</L>
<L>And in this erth also his body was solde,</L>
<L>Here in this erth, whan &thorn;at he was XXX<SUP>ti</SUP> &yogh;ere olde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<L>God lytyd in erth, blyssed be that stounde!<MILESTONE N="68b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He sauyd hys herth with many a scharpe wounde;</L>
<L>For to sawe erth owght of hell grounde,</L>
<L>He deyd in erth vpon &thorn;e rode with many a blody vounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And god ros ovght of the est this erth forto spede</L>
<L>And went into hell, as was gret nede,</L>
<L>And toke erth from sorowe, &thorn;us<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>? Ms</I>. y&es; = &thorn;us <I>oder</I> &thorn;is?</NOTE> erth forto spede &mdash;</L>
<L>The ryght wey to heuen blys Iesus Cryst vs lede! Amen.<NOTE PLACE="end">Darunter gute buntfarbige Zeichnung: Ein bl&uuml;hender Junker in reichem Gewande und blonden Locken steht auf einem gr&uuml;nen Grash&uuml;gel, in welchem gerade unter ihm ein Gerippe liegt. Um das Ganze schlingen sich B&auml;nder mit den Inschriften: 1. ffestina tempus et memento finis; 2. In omni opere memorare nouissima et in eternum non peccabis.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&sect; 2.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="editorial note">
<HEAD>Noch nicht benutzte anglo-irische Handschriften.</HEAD>
<P>Sichere und rein anglo-irische Hss. kann ich aus der Bibliothek des Lambeth-Palace in London in je einer neuen Version von Conquest of Ireland und Secreta Secretorum nach|weisen. Eine dritte sp&auml;tere Lambeth-Hs. aus dem 16. Jahr|hundert, obwohl unrein und von der Schriftsprache st&auml;rker 
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="216"> beeinflu&szlig;t, ist sicher in Irland geschrieben, wie schon aus der Zusammensetzung dieser irischen Materialsammlung, aber auch aus den sprachlichen Eigent&uuml;mlichkeiten hervorgeht. Das einzelne Pergamentblatt aus der Hs. Laud 526 der Bodl. ist sicher anglo-irisch, wenn auch in ziemlich verwilderter Sprache &uuml;berliefert. Zweifelhaft k&ouml;nnte dagegen das Urteil &uuml;ber ein Oxforder Ms. von Piers the Plowman erscheinen, da hier keinerlei &auml;u&szlig;ere Gr&uuml;nde auf Irland weisen (? Tutivillus). Auch die Sprache ist nicht rein, da der Einflu&szlig; der Vorlage sich sehr stark bemerkbar macht. Trotzdem scheint mir der Schreiber ein Anglo-ire zu sein, wie konsequentes <I>&thorn;rogh</I> (= <I>through</I>) und <I>scho</I> (= <I>she</I>), h&auml;ufiges <I>&thorn;ai, har, ham</I> (neben dem aus der Vorlage stammenden <I>&thorn;ey, her, hem</I>), <I>leyn</I>(<I>gh</I>)<I>th</I> und <I>streynth</I>, vor allem aber auch Verstummen des auslaut. -<I>e</I> bei s&uuml;dlichen Formen (regelm. <I>hit</I>) und Doppelschreibung von Konsonanten in <I>tholled, brekke&thorn;, berre</I> etc. beweist. Die anglo-irischen Eigent&uuml;mlichkeiten pr&auml;gen sich in der Sprache dieses Denk|mals viel sch&auml;rfer aus, als in den Gedichten gegen die Friars (cf. S. 75), die vielleicht besser weggeblieben w&auml;ren. Ich werde daher auch von diesem Denkmal, das Skeat unter den C-texten seiner Ausgabe erw&auml;hnt, Proben mitteilen, um es wenigstens notd&uuml;rftig zug&auml;ngig zu machen.</P></DIV3>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="manuscript source">
<HEAD>I. Ms. Lambeth 598 (Pergament, 15. Jahrhundert).</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="editorial note">
<P>Enth&auml;lt auf fol. 1-30 die bereits nach anderen Hss. ver|&ouml;ffentlichte Eroberung von Irland. Der Text scheint den beiden Hss. der E.E.T.S. gleichwertig zu sein. Am Schlusse (fol. 30b) ist in anderer Schrift hinzugef&uuml;gt: secundum Thomam Bray.</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="prose extract">
<HEAD>Cf. Conquest of Ireland, E.E.T.S. 107, p. 73 (Rawl. Ms.).</HEAD>
<P>Cap. 30. Undyr this, as the land of Irland was yn good<MILESTONE N="14b" UNIT="folio"> pees vndir ham that weryne left the lond forto kepe, byfell on a day that a certeyn place to a parlement was sette betwen Hughe de Lacy, to whom the kyng hade yewe Deulyne to kepe with trust, and the kyng of Mythe. On a nyght, whan the parlement shold bene a morowe, a knyght, that was Morych Fiz Geraudes eme and Robert Gryffyn by name, thoght in his sleppe that he sawe a miche flotte of wyld swyne yernyng vppon Hughe and Moryche and a bor among ham myche and 
<PB REF="00000225.tif" N="217"> grymly ouer al othir come to<NOTE PLACE="foot">to ham</NOTE> and with his tuskes wold haue smytten and ham slayn, yef he boldly ne hade come betwen and slayn the bore and holpid ham both. On the morowe thay went vnto the place, ther the parlement was, at a<MILESTONE N="15" UNIT="folio"> place that sithin ys callid O Roykes hyll.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Rorike-is hille</NOTE> Frust thay heldyn thar parlement from fer by messagres goyng betwen; ther aftyr thay tokc<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. tok</NOTE> surte and othis swar and comyne togaddyr aftirward. Natheles fewe and ylyk many on euery syd, and thay vnweppned, but the one ther swerdes, the othir thar sparys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sparthes</NOTE> and her felawchippe on euery syde fro tham.<NOTE PLACE="foot">fere fro ham</NOTE> Gryffyn, that with Moryce come to the parlement, was ful thoghtfull of the vysycion<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. vysy&cmacr;&omacr;n</NOTE> that he sawe; he name to hym VII knyghtis of his owyne kyne, tham that he most trust to har bolnys, and drowyn ham on the one halff of the hylle, as ney as thay myght leppyn vppene thar stedes with cheldes about har nekkes and speres yn hand, and for oon purposse pleydyn and prykkiden yn the felld ayeyne othir, so that yn what syde the parlement turneden, throgh encheyson of suche play thay myght be fondyne redy. Roryk and Hugh kepte thar parlement of many thynges, but yn no thyng thay myght acord and begone to depart as yn wreth. The traytour Roryk hade yn his thoght the treysone that he hade purueyd. He made semblant and hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">drow hym</NOTE> besydes as forto pyssen and made tokyn to his men that thay hastely shold come vnto hym. Whan he this hade doone, he turnyd ayene with his spar<NOTE PLACE="foot">sparth</NOTE> an hey, his face al blak with ful snell goyng. Moryche was warnyd of his eme by the vysycion that he sawe, stode and beheld al this; he tok out his swerd and cryed vppon Hughe and mynd<NOTE PLACE="foot">mynyd</NOTE> hym and dyde hyme selff agayn the traytour forto defend hym. The traytour rane agayne Hughe hym for to smyte; har latymer yede betwen hym and the strok, and he smote of hym the oon arme of, fast by the shuldir. Moryce stod and camplyd with his swerde ayeyne the spar and loude cryed to har men. And har Hugh myght be in anny state hym selff forto defend, throgh gret hastyng he fell doune<NOTE PLACE="foot">doune <I>fehlt</I></NOTE> twies a bac [&amp;]<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; <I>&uuml;bergeschrieben im Ms.?</I></NOTE> vnneth throght helpe of Moryce that hym defendid thus escapyd with 
<PB REF="00000226.tif" N="218"> his lyff. The whyll that this was, Rorykes men ful many come to his callyng out of dalis and woddes, about rynnyng to ham with speres and sparrys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sparthes</NOTE> forto berewe Hughe and Moryce the lyff. Than Gryffyn and his felawis come rynnynge vppon har hors styffly to ham; the traytour sawe ham commyng and lepe to hors that hym was broght and wold do hym to flyght, and as he lepe vppe, come Gryffyn and with his sper smote hyme and his hors throgh out and <ABBR>slaye</ABBR> tham. Withe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&uuml;ber</I> withe <I>ist etwas &uuml;bergeschrieben</I></NOTE> hym wer slayne thay that yn so myche pereyll the hors hym broght, and his hede smytten of, and ynto England theraftyr to the kynge hit send, and al his men into al &thorn;e felddis dide<NOTE PLACE="foot">dide <I>fehlt</I></NOTE> discomfyd and slayne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. <ABBR>slaye</ABBR>.</NOTE> ful many. Rolff Robertes sone Fiz Steuuyn was the othir boldist &thorn;at day yn the feld. &mdash;</P>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="manuscript source">
<HEAD>II. Ms. Lambeth 633 (Pergament, 15. saec.).</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="editorial note">
<P>84 Bl&auml;tter, sehr sch&ouml;n geschrieben, echt anglo - irische Schreibung, Text dem in E.E.T.S. ver&ouml;ffentlichten gleichwertig.</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="prose extract">
<HEAD>cf. Secreta Secretorum E.E.T.S. Extra Series 74, p. 189.</HEAD>
<P>This moch haue I said of this vertu Temporans for this<MILESTONE N="45" UNIT="folio"> tym. Now her I write old storiens<NOTE PLACE="foot">stories</NOTE> in commendacioun of the sam vertu. Capitulum XXX<SUP>m</SUP> quintum.</P>
<P>Aristotle, prince of Philosofers, saith that to the vertu of temporance two thinges appartenyth, that is to witte: Abstinence of met and drink and chastite of body. And<MILESTONE N="45b" UNIT="folio"> therfor old wertius men this two thinges thay kepeden. This apperith by this story. Alexander, the conquerour, so mych he myght endure abstinence that oft <ABBR>tymys</ABBR>, whan he was in trawayll, he asked non othir met but bred only. A gret clerk Vegece vs tellith in his bok of cheualri, that hit appartenyth not to a gode knyght to lowe es<NOTE PLACE="foot">ayse</NOTE> no delittes of body. Als moch is abstinence auenaunt to a kny&yogh;t and messure, as to a monk. Valeri tellith that wemen of Rom in old tym dranke 
<PB REF="00000227.tif" N="219"> no whyn, ffor throghe glottonny and dronkenys men fallith ofte tymys in luchury which ys contrari to chastite and to chevalri. And therfor, as Waleri tellith, that Cornelius Scipion, whan he was send by the Romannus into Spayn to mak hit subiette<NOTE PLACE="foot">subiecte</NOTE> to Rom, anon he comaunddit that no brothell wher found in har companny, and therfor thowo<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ebenfalls</I> thowo</NOTE> thousand wemen weren drywin away from the oste. Well wiste the vies prince that loue of wemen and branding fylthed of lechuri nesshith a man is hert and hym makith lik a woman, so that he lesseth his strei[n]th and hardinis and manhod and chewalri. Mor acordith to a lechurer a stef staf than a swerd, and an hechill than on sheld<NOTE PLACE="foot">an chelde</NOTE> othir a bukelere. And therfor saith poetes in fabill that the well of Salynace maketh men, that ther in ham bathith, chaunge in to wemen, In singnificaunce and token that tho men which ham bathith in the well of lechuri lessith wertu and walure and becomyth feint and cowardis and febill, as wemen ben. The sam clerk Valeri vs tellith of a nobill yong man that was calit Spurius, that was so ffair of face, of body and fetares,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ebenfalls</I> fetares</NOTE> that all wemen were meuet and temptid of his gret beaute. This yong man<MILESTONE N="46" UNIT="folio"> that well parcewid, but he had no talent of foly. And therfor, als moch as he wold not be suspecte of foly ne yew occasioun ne cheissoun of ille and syn, he woundit all his face and many wo&umacr;nddes ther in maked, wherfor the beaute away went and the syn seissit. The lossit clerk Vegesce of kyng Alexander tellith that after a gret battaill ydon and gret pray taken a nobill damsell off gret beaute was pre|senttid to the kyng. But he that al was yevin to chiualry, he nad no cure of lechury. And therfor he endeynet not ons hyr to reward, but send hir to the sam prince that she affor was spoussed to. Whan this prince and his men saue this, thay praysid moch the wertu and the gret leaute of Alexander, and ther thay hym recevid as kyng and lord. Such anothir tall vs telith Walery and saith that at that tym, whan Scipion had won and conquerit Cortage, as is in this bok aforvrittin, among all othir ostages a fair maid of gret Porache<NOTE PLACE="foot">Paroge</NOTE> to hym was presentid. And whan this conquerour had vndirstand that 
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="220"> a Ientilman of the contre had hir trouthid, he maked bring afor hym hir fadir and hir moder and the Ientilman that hir trouthid. And to ham saide he:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. saidene</NOTE> "This gold that ye haue broght to me for this damsell is ransoun, I hit yew and graunt in free mariage to hir and to this Ientillman that hir has trouthid." Of this grette Ientrie all men mervelith and this nobill lord mor gladly for ay servid. By this vertu Temporancia a man gouernyth hym self, and with the vertu of Iustice othir men. But rathir and more providabill ys to<MILESTONE N="46b" UNIT="folio"> a man to gouern hym self than othir mene.</P>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="manuscript source">
<HEAD>III. Ms. Lambeth 623 (Pergament, Sammelhs. des 16. saec.).</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="editorial note"><P>Von den mannigfachen, hier zusammengebundenen St&uuml;cken des 2. Teiles (177 Bl&auml;tter), sind als wichtigste zu nennen (nach dem Katalog):</P><P>An old book of the Conquest of Ireland fol. 6-60, daraus die mitgeteilte Probe, vorher geht fol. 1-5 Description of Ireland etc.</P><P>Sir John Plunket's Book relating to Ireland (fol. 60-101), (z. T. annalenm&auml;&szlig;ig nach Jahreszahlen geordnet).</P><P>Walter Hussey's Book relating to Ireland (who died in 1554) fol. 108-121.</P><P>Der Rest (fol. 102-108 und 120-177) wird im Katalog sehr mit Recht als: confused collection relating to Ireland bezeichnet; erw&auml;hnenswert ist daraus: A fragment of the History of Ireland fol. 149-151.</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="prose extract">
<HEAD>Cf. Conquest of Ireland, E.E.T.S. 107, p. 130 (geringf&uuml;gige Abweichungen im Text).</HEAD>
<P>Aboute that tym befell a wondere adwenture<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. wonders adwenturs?</NOTE> in a<MILESTONE N="47" UNIT="folio"> wodde in Mythe off a prest &thorn;at went by the way, and as he came throgh &thorn;at wodde, ther came a man agaynste him and bad him for gode sacke and lowe that he shuld turne with him, for to shriue his wiffe that laye seke ther. The prest 
<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="221"> torned with him, and when he came somwhat neye, he hard groninge and waylinge, as thogh hit wer off a woman; and when he cam right ther, then was hit a wolff that laye ther groninge. The prist saw that and was well sore afrayed and turned him awaye. The man and the wolff bothe spacke vnto him and bade him that he shuld not be afrayed and that he shulde turne to her to hire confecion. &THORN;e prist toke hart to him and blessyd him and went and satt besydes her, and the wolff spacke to him and confessyd her to the prist; and when they had &thorn;at done, the prist remembrit him sylff that such a evel shapen thinge shuld haw swche grace for to specke. But yet throgh gode will he moght haw suche grace sheved vnto him and insyght off othere thinge. He satt doune and asked &thorn;e wolff off the outcommen men callid &thorn;e Inglishe men &thorn;at in to &thorn;e land wer commen, how hit shold behape off them. &THORN;e wolff ansuered and sayd &thorn;at for &thorn;e sine off &thorn;e peopell off &thorn;e land almighty god was angre with them and sent &thorn;at<MILESTONE N="47b" UNIT="folio"> peopell for to bringe them in to thraldome, and so they shuld contynue, vntyll &thorn;e same peopell had repentyd ther synnis, and then they shuld haw pouere for to be delywered off ther thraldome and wreched lyffe.</P>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="manuscript source">
<HEAD>IV. Ms. Laud 526.</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="editorial note"><P>Ein einzelnes Pergamentblatt, das letzte im Ms. Der Text und die Schreibung sind ziemlich verwahrlost. Dasselbe Zeichen dient f&uuml;r konsonant. <I>y</I> und <I>&thorn;</I>, vokal. und konsonant. y unter|scheiden sich durch einen Schn&ouml;rkel; doch ist auch &yogh; vor|handen, z. T. selbst f&uuml;r &thorn; gebraucht (cf. 4mal <I>o&yogh;is</I>).</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="prose extract">
<HEAD>Cf. Conquest of Ireland, E.E.T.S. 107, p. 134.</HEAD>
<P>It&es; &thorn;e titil &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng of Ingelonde hath to Irland.</P>
<P>[W]han<NOTE PLACE="foot">W <I>abgeschnitten</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;e kynges son had rayede all &thorn;yng &thorn;at vas for honour to cum into Irland, he cam ynto Mylforth, and &thorn;er he toke scippyn; he landit at Waterford on &thorn;e morrowe. &thorn;er cam with hym .CCC. kny&yogh;tys and dyuerse sauyouers.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. sauyou's</NOTE> He aryvyt 
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="222"> &thorn;e &yogh;ere of his fadyre ys held .XXII., Of his fadire is comyng yn to Irland .XIII., Of the Erle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. Erld?</NOTE> is comyng .XIV., Of Robert Stevuenyson is comyng .XV., The yere of our lord is incarna|cioun .MCLXXXV. Robert Stevuenysson vas forman to &thorn;e erle and oppynet &thorn;e vay, &thorn;e Erle to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lies</I> com (= c&omacr;)</NOTE> to the kyng, The kyng to his son. And mych hit is to prayse hym &thorn;at fyrste cam into Irland so boldly &thorn;at all &thorn;ing fulle endit and &thorn;e lordeschepe wan before all o&thorn;er. Men may vell vndirestond &thorn;at Englisch men hayth vary ry&yogh;gthe onto Irland. And all &thorn;e princes of the land yald ham selffe onto &thorn;e kyng wit hare own gode vill, to be euermore sugetes to hym and to all his. Opon all &thorn;is &thorn;e pope of Rome &thorn;at is hed of all cristyndom, he<NOTE PLACE="foot">and that hath</NOTE> hayth a speciale ryght to all Iles as vyde as &thorn;e worle. And<NOTE PLACE="foot">he yaf plenerly and</NOTE> con|firmyt to &thorn;e kyng &thorn;e lordschepe of &thorn;e said land, as is tofor told. And of eldyre ryght we fyndith wrytt &thorn;at &thorn;e kynges of Englon hayth to Irland of Dermovnd<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>D</I> Germon, <I>R</I> Gormon</NOTE> Belynes son, kyng of Birtayn, &thorn;at is nov callit Englon, he cam yn to Irland and wane &thorn;e land and many yer bare hym truage, And o&thorn;eris after hym in to Byrtayn. &thorn;er after &thorn;e kyng Arture had tryvage<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. tryvag</NOTE> oute of Irland, and Gylmory &thorn;e kyng &thorn;at was with o&thorn;er kynges of &thorn;e Ilandes was with hym at &thorn;e grett feste &thorn;at he held at Carllyovn. On o&thorn;er halfe &thorn;e folke of Irland cam formost oute of Bastiles and oute of Bayovne &thorn;at longyth nowe (to)<NOTE PLACE="foot">(to), <I>im Ms. Klecks</I></NOTE> Gas|quyne, Were of kynges of Englon ben lordis. And &thorn;is men may vndirestand, &thorn;at goyth<NOTE PLACE="foot">both</NOTE> by olde ryght and by neve, &thorn;e kynges of Englon o&yogh;t to hawe &thorn;e lordscheppe off Irland, and also &thorn;ai &yogh;alde ham selfe to kyng Harry fi&yogh;t emperis and by grett o&yogh;is and ostagisse. And &thorn;e pope acursit &thorn;o &thorn;at were aganys the kyng. And &thorn;e&yogh;e &thorn;ay &thorn;roghe kynd<NOTE PLACE="foot">? <I>Ms</I>. kyne</NOTE> falssenes and vnstabillnyse &thorn;at yn ham is &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at <I>fehlt</I></NOTE> lityll tell of o&yogh;is and of worscheppe. And &thorn;ai stand acurssit of &thorn;e pope fore the brekyn of hare fayth and hare o&yogh;is. Thay ware nevire assolitt ne vnbownd of hare o&yogh;is. Man may bynd hym selffe with such &thorn;ynges, bot not so lyghtly hym selffe vnbyn. Et cetera.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>so im Ms</I>.</NOTE>
</P>

</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="manuscript source"><PB REF="00000231.tif" N="223">
<HEAD>V. Ms. Douce 104, Bodleiana (Pergament, 15. saec.).</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>ed. Rel. Ant. I, 257.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tutiuillus, &thorn;e deuyl of hell',<MILESTONE N="112b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He wryte&thorn; har names, so&thorn;e to tel,</L>
<L>admissa [extrahantes].</L>
<L>Better wer be at tome for ay</L>
<L>&THORN;an her to serue &thorn;e deuil to pay,</L>
<L>sit vana [famulantes].</L>
<L>&THORN;os<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;oS <I>unter Klecks</I>.</NOTE> women &thorn;at sitte&thorn; &thorn;e church about,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai be&thorn; al of &thorn;e deuelis rowte,</L>
<L>diuina [inpotentes].</L>
<L>But &thorn;ai be stil, he wil ham quell,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; kene crokes draw hem to hell,</L>
<L>ad pacienciam flentes.</L>
<L>For hys loue &thorn;at &yogh;ou der bo&yogh;th,</L>
<L>Hold &yogh;ou stil and Iangel no&yogh;th,</L>
<L>sord[em aperte deprecantes]!</L>
<L>&THORN;e blis of heuen &thorn;an may &yogh;e wyn,</L>
<L>God bryng vs al to his In,</L>
<L>amen [semper] dicentes!</L>
<L>Vnde Beda:</L>
<L>Qui osculetur meretricem, pulsat campanam inferni.</L>
</LG>
<P>Die lateinischen Stellen finden sich auf beschmutzter Stelle im Ms. und sind zum gro&szlig;en Teil wenig leserlich; ich folge darin Wright, bin aber vielfach zweifelhaft (vgl. die Klammern).</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Cf. E. E. T. S. 54, p. 46.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nesciat dextera, quid faciat sinistra.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So im Ms.!</I></NOTE><MILESTONE N="12a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Let no&yogh;t &thorn;i lyft hand: our lord teche&thorn;,</L>
<L>Wit what delyst: wi&thorn; &thorn;i ri&yogh;th syde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it mede &thorn;e meyre: mildely beso&yogh;th&mdash;</L>
<L>Bo&thorn; schereues and sariauntes: and such as kepe&thorn; &thorn;e law,</L>
<L>To punchen<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. punyshen</NOTE> oppon pilories: and oppon pynnyng stokes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. pynyng-stoles</NOTE></L>
<L>As bakers and brewers: bouchers and kokes&mdash;
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="224"></L>
<L>For &thorn;os men do&thorn; most harme: to &thorn;e mene pepil,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;th &thorn;ro&yogh;th regratry: rentes ham byggi&thorn;,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e pore pepil: schuld put in har wombe.</L>
<L>For tok &thorn;ei euer trewly: &thorn;ai tymbrid no&yogh;th so hey,</L>
<L>Ne bo&yogh;th no&yogh;th burgages: be &yogh;e ful certayn.</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;ai haue no pite on &thorn;e pepil: &thorn;at parcelmel most byg;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o&yogh;th &thorn;ei tak hem vntydi &thorn;yng: no treysoun &thorn;ei ne holt hit;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o&yogh;th &thorn;ai sil<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. fulle</NOTE> no&yogh;th ful: &thorn;at for law is seled,</L>
<L>He grypi&thorn; &thorn;er for a grot: as for gray&thorn; trow&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. grete treuthe</NOTE></L>
<L>Many sondry sorowes: in cytees falle&thorn; ofte,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn; &thorn;ro&yogh;th fire and &thorn;ro&yogh;th flode: and &thorn;ro&yogh;&thorn; fals pepil,</L>
<L>&THORN;at begili&thorn; gode men: and greue&thorn; hem wrongly.</L>
<L>&THORN;e woch &thorn;at cried on her knees: &thorn;at Crist hem avenge</L>
<L>Her on &thorn;is er&thorn;e: or ellys in hell',</L>
<L>&THORN;at so begili&thorn; hem of her gode: &thorn;at god hem sende<MILESTONE N="12b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Feuer o&thorn;er foul euel: o&thorn;er fire on her houses,</L>
<L>Moreyn or o&thorn;er myschef: and many tymes hit falle&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Innocens is herd: In heuen among seyntes</L>
<L>&THORN;at loude cried for hem: to our lorde and to our lady bo&thorn;,</L>
<L>Graunt<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. To graunten</NOTE> to gylours on er&thorn;e: grace to amend.</L>
<L>And haue her penans on pur er&thorn;e: and no&yogh;th in peyn<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. &thorn;e pyne</NOTE> of hel'.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an falle&thorn; &thorn;e fire: on fals menus<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. men&es;</NOTE> howses,</L>
<L>And gode mennus for her gylt: gloue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. glowe&thorn;</NOTE> on fire after.</L>
<L>All &thorn;is haue we seen: &thorn;at sum tyme &thorn;ro&yogh;th a brewer</L>
<L>Many burgages ha&thorn; be brant: and bodyes &thorn;er In,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ro&yogh;th a candel clemyng<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. clomyng</NOTE>: in a corsed place</L>
<L>Fel adoun and forbrent: for&thorn; al a rew.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. &thorn;e rewe</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;i meyres &thorn;at make&thorn; fremen: me &thorn;ynk &thorn;at &yogh;o<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. &thorn;ei</NOTE> o&yogh;th</L>
<L>For to sper and aspy: for ony spech of siluer,</L>
<L>What maner mester: or marchondis he vse&thorn;,</L>
<L>Or he wer vndirfong fre: and felew in &yogh;our rollys.</L>
<L>Hit is no&yogh;th semely for so&thorn;e: in cyte and in burgh toun</L>
<L>&THORN;at vsurreris and regraters: for ony kyn &yogh;iftes</L>
<L>Be franchesed for a fre man: and haue a fals name.</L>
<L>Ac Mede &thorn;e maide: &thorn;e maire ho beso&yogh;th</L>
<L>Of al such<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. suth; ch <I>und</I> th, ct <I>und</I> tt <I>sind oft nicht zu unter|scheiden</I>.</NOTE> sillers: siluer to take
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="225"></L>
<L>Or presentes wi&thorn; out pans: and o&thorn;er priue &yogh;iftis,</L>
<L>Haue rew&thorn;e of regratours: &thorn;at haue riche handis.</L>
<L>In quorum manibus iniquitates sunt.</L>
<L>"Loue ham for my loue": quod &thorn;is lady Mede,</L>
<L>"And suffer ham sum tyme: to syll a&yogh;enes &thorn;e law".</L>
<L>Salamon &thorn;e sage, a sermond he made,</L>
<L>In amendement of mayres: and o&thorn;er stiwardes,</L>
<L>And wittenesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. witnessyth</NOTE> what wor&thorn; of hem: &thorn;at wol tak med.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5b" TYPE="source">
<HEAD>V b.</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Cf. E. E. T. S. 54, p. 52.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sunt infelices, qui[a] matres sunt meretrices.<MILESTONE N="13b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ere scho is weld<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. wel</NOTE> wi&thorn; ony kyng: wo is &thorn;e reme,</L>
<L>For scho is fauorable to &thorn;e fals: &thorn;e woch defoule&thorn; trow&thorn;e.</L>
<L>By Iesus wi&thorn; hir Iuweles: &thorn;e Iustice scho scheue&thorn;;</L>
<L>Scho lye&thorn; a&yogh;enes &thorn;e law: and lette&thorn; hym &thorn;e gate,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fai&thorn;e may<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. may not haue hus for&thorn;: hure florines ...</NOTE> haue no for&thorn;: for florens go&thorn; so &thorn;yck;</L>
<L>And lede&thorn; &thorn;e law as hir lust: &thorn;at lewte my&yogh;t wyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk. abweichend, = 2 Verse</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;e mase<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. The mase</NOTE> for a mene man: &thorn;e&yogh;th he mote euer.</L>
<L>Law is so lordely: and lo&yogh;th to mak an ende,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; out presentes o&thorn;er pans: he plese&thorn; ful few.<MILESTONE N="14" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Trew burgeis and bond: to no&yogh;t scho brynge&thorn; oft,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e comune in care: and in couetys;</L>
<L>Religioun scho al torent and out of rule to libbe.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere is<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. nys</NOTE> cyte vnder sone: ne non so riche reume,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere scho is lowed or let by: &thorn;at last schal ony whyle,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; outen wer o&thorn;er wo: o&thorn;er wyked lawes</L>
<L>And costomes of couetys: &thorn;e comune to distrw.</L>
<L>Vnsittyng sufferans: hir suster, and hir sylf</L>
<L>Han al most mad: but Mary &thorn;e help,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e lond ne loue&thorn; &thorn;e: and &yogh;it lest &thorn;yn ouen.</L>
<L>For clerkes and couetys: mede ha&thorn; knet togyders,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e wit of &thorn;e world: is waxen to gyle.</L>
<L>&THORN;us lede&thorn; &thorn;is lady &thorn;i lond: now, lord, &yogh;if hir sorow!
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="226"></L>
<L>For pore men dar no&yogh;th pleyn: ne non pleynt schew,</L>
<L>Such a maister is mede: among men of gode!</L>
<L>&THORN;an mourned scho and mened hir to &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>To haue space to spek: sped &yogh;if scho my&yogh;th.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng graunt hir grace: wi&thorn; a god will.</L>
<L>"Excuse &thorn;e, &yogh;if &thorn;ou canst: I can no mor sig;</L>
<L>For consciens accusce&thorn; &thorn;e: to conge &thorn;e for euer."</L>
<L>"Nay lord", quod &thorn;at lady: "leue hym &thorn;e wors,</L>
<L>Whan ye wote witterly: in whom &thorn;e wrang lyge&thorn;.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere &thorn;at myschef is gret: mede may help.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou knowest, consciens: I can no&yogh;t chide,</L>
<L>Ne depraue &thorn;i persone: wi&thorn; a proud hert.</L>
<L>Wel &thorn;ou wost whi: but &thorn;ou wilt gab,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast hanget at my half:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. hals</NOTE> eleuen tymes,</L>
<L>And al so gryp<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. grypen of</NOTE> my gold: and gyuen it, wer &thorn;e like&thorn;.</L>
<L>Why &thorn;ou wre&thorn;est &thorn;e now: wondir me &thorn;ynke&thorn;,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it y may, as y my&yogh;th: menske &thorn;e wi&thorn; &yogh;iftis</L>
<L>And mayntene &thorn;i manhod: mor &thorn;an &thorn;ou knowest.</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ou hast famed me foule: byfor &thorn;e kyng here.</L>
<L>For kylde I neuer no kyng: ne consail<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. consailed</NOTE> so to don,</L>
<L>Ac y haue saued my sylf: sexty<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. and sexty</NOTE> &thorn;ousand lyues,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn; here and ellys where: In al kyn londes.</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ou &thorn;i sylf sothely: who so hit sig durst,<MILESTONE N="14b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hast hartyd<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. arwed</NOTE> many hardy man: &thorn;at had wil to fy&yogh;th,</L>
<L>To brent and to bowen:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. To brennen and to bruten</NOTE> to beten doun streynghes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. strengthes</NOTE></L>
<L>In contrees &thorn;er &thorn;e kyng come: consciens hem<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. hym</NOTE> let,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he fell<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. felde</NOTE> no&yogh;th his foes: &thorn;o fortune hit wold,</L>
<L>And as his wardys wer ordeyned: at &thorn;e wil of our lord.</L>
<L>Kaytifly &thorn;ou, consciens: consayled<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. consailedist</NOTE> &thorn;e kyng to lett</L>
<L>In his enemys handis: his eritage of Fraunce.</L>
<L>Vnkyndely is &thorn;at, consciens: a kyngdom to syll,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. &thorn;at yse</NOTE> conquerit &thorn;ro&yogh;th a commune help: a kyngdom or a duchery.</L>
<L>Hit may no&yogh;t be sold so li&yogh;thely so many part<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. here part</NOTE> axe&thorn;</L>
<L>At<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. Of, <I>Ms</I>. ac</NOTE> folk &thorn;at fe&yogh;th &thorn;ere for: and folowt &thorn;e kynges wyl.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lest lad &thorn;at longe&thorn; wi&thorn; hym:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. to hym</NOTE> be &thorn;e lond won,
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="227"></L>
<L>Loke&thorn; aftyr lordchip: or ellis large mede,</L>
<L>Wher by he may as a man for euer more liue after.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is &thorn;e kynd of a kyng: &thorn;at conquere&thorn; on<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. of</NOTE> his enemys,</L>
<L>To help ylich<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. heyeliche</NOTE> al his ost: or ellis graunt</L>
<L>&THORN;at al his men may<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. mowen</NOTE> wyn: do &thorn;ere wi&thorn; har best.</L>
<L>For &thorn;i I consaile no kyng: ony consail aske</L>
<L>At consciens &thorn;at coueti&thorn;:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. yf he c.</NOTE> to conquer a reume.</L>
<L>For schuld neuer consciens be my consaile: "wer I kyng", quod mede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>etwas ge&auml;ndert, Sk. hat 2 Reihen</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Ne be marechal ouer my men: &thorn;er y most fi&yogh;th.</L>
<L>Ac had y, mede, be his marachal: ouer his men in Fraunce,</L>
<L>I durst haue leid my lif: and no las wed,</L>
<L>He schold haue Ibe lorde of &thorn;at londe: of leyng&thorn; and of brede etc.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Cf. E. E. T. S. 54, p. 139.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod<NOTE PLACE="foot">Quod <I>ausgeschrieben</I></NOTE> Perkyn &thorn;e ploughman: "be seint Peter of Rome,<MILESTONE N="35a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I haue an half acre to ere: by &thorn;e hey wey.</L>
<L>Had I erred &thorn;is half acre: and sowed affter,</L>
<L>I wold wend wi&thorn; &yogh;ou: and &thorn;e hey way tech."</L>
<L>"&THORN;at were a long lettyng": quod a lady in a schare,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. skleire</NOTE></L>
<L>What schuld we women: worch in &thorn;e whiles?"</L>
<L>"I pray &yogh;ou for &yogh;our profite": quod Peres to &thorn;e ladyes,</L>
<L>"&THORN;at sum sow &thorn;e sake: ffor schedyng of &thorn;e whete;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. &yogh;e</NOTE> worthy women: wi&thorn; &yogh;our long fyngers</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e on silk an<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>so Ms</I>.</NOTE> on sendel: sew, whan tyme is,</L>
<L>Chesebles for chapelens: churches to honour.</L>
<L>Wyffes and wodowes: wol and flex spynnen;</L>
<L>Consciens consaile&thorn; &yogh;ou: clo&thorn;e for to make,</L>
<L>For profite of &thorn;e pore: and plesaunce of &yogh;our silfen.</L>
<L>For y schal lene hem liflod: but &thorn;e lond faile,</L>
<L>As long as I lyue: for &thorn;e lordis loue of heuene.</L>
<L>And al maner men: &thorn;at by &thorn;e mold susteyne&thorn;,</L>
<L>Helpe&thorn; hem to worch witterly: &thorn;at wynnen &yogh;our fode."<MILESTONE N="35b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"By Cryst", quod a kne&yogh;th &thorn;o: "he kenne&thorn; vs &thorn;e beste,
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="228"></L>
<L>Ac a[l] &thorn;at tyme trewly: taugh<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. on &thorn;e teeme trewely: tauht</NOTE> was I neuer.</L>
<L>I wold, y cou&thorn;e", said &thorn;e kne&yogh;th: "by Crist and his modir,</L>
<L>I wold assay sum tyme: for solas as hit were."</L>
<L>"Sikirly, sir kne&yogh;th": said Peres &thorn;an,</L>
<L>"I schald<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. shal</NOTE> swynke and swete: and sow for vs bo&thorn;</L>
<L>And labour for &thorn;o &thorn;at &thorn;ou louest: al my<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. for &thorn;e while &thorn;ou lyuest al &thorn;y . .</NOTE> liue tyme,</L>
<L>In couenante &thorn;at &thorn;ou kep: holy kyrke and my silfe</L>
<L>For wastours and fro wicked men: &thorn;at &thorn;is world strue&thorn;.</L>
<L>And go hunte hardely: to hares and to foxes,</L>
<L>To berres<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. bores</NOTE> and to buckes: &thorn;at br[e]kke&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ms</I>. bkke&thorn; (<I>Sk</I>. breke&thorn;)</NOTE> adoun my hegges,</L>
<L>And affaite &thorn;i facouns: to kyl &thorn;e wyle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. wylde</NOTE> fowles,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ei come&thorn; to my croft: my corne to defoule." etc.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Cf. E. E. T. S. 54, p. 264.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Omnis sanctus in tempore oportuno.<MILESTONE N="67a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an consciens comford vs: bo&thorn; clerge and scriptour</L>
<L>And seide "Cor contritum et humiliatum: deus, non despicies".</L>
<L>Paciens was wel apaide: of &thorn;is propir seruice,</L>
<L>And mad myry wi&thorn; &thorn;is mette: ac I mourned euer,</L>
<L>For a doctour at &thorn;e hey dees: drank wyne faste &mdash;</L>
<L>Ve vobis qui potentes estis: ad bibendum vinum &mdash;</L>
<L>And ete many sondry mettes: morturus<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. mortrews</NOTE> and podynges,</L>
<L>Braune and blod of gees: bacoun and colopus.</L>
<L>&THORN;an said I to my silf: so paciens hit herde:</L>
<L>"Hit is no&yogh;th &thorn;re dayes don: &thorn;is doctour &thorn;at he preched</L>
<L>At Poules byfor &thorn;e pepil: what penance &thorn;ei suffered,<MILESTONE N="67b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>All &thorn;at couete to come: to any kyn Ioy,</L>
<L>And how Poule &thorn;e appostil: what penance he &thorn;olled</L>
<L>For our lordis loue, as holy letter telli&thorn;:</L>
<L>"In fame and frig[ore]"</L>
<L>Ac me wondere&thorn; in my witte: why &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne preche&thorn;,</L>
<L>As Poul &thorn;e appostil: preched to &thorn;e pepill ofte</L>
<L>"Periculum est in falsis fratribus!"</L>
<L>Holy writte biddi&thorn; men be war: and wysely hem kepe,
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="229"></L>
<L>&THORN;at no fals frere: &thorn;rogh flateryng hem begyle.</L>
<L>Ac me &thorn;ynke&thorn; lo&thorn;e &thorn;o&yogh;th: &thorn;o&yogh; I latyn knew, to lac any sect,</L>
<L>For al be we bretheren: &thorn;o&yogh;th we be diuerse clo&thorn;ed.</L>
<L>Ac I wist neuer freke, &thorn;at frere is Icalled:</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e four mendinauntz<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. Of &thorn;e fyue mendynauns . and made eny sarmon</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at tok hit for his teme: and told hit wi&thorn; out glose.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei preche&thorn; &thorn;at penaunce: is profitable to &thorn;e soule,</L>
<L>And what mychef and male ese: Crist for man &thorn;olled.</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;is doctour and diuinour, quod I, and decretister of canoun<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. canon, <I>Ms</I>. canom</NOTE></L>
<L>And also a gredy glotoun: wi&thorn; two grete chekes,</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; no pite of vs pore: he perfowrome&thorn; euel.</L>
<L>"&THORN;at he preche&thorn;, he proue&thorn; no&yogh;th:" paciens I tolde</L>
<L>And wissed<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sk</I>. wisshede</NOTE> witterly: wi&thorn; wil ful egre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e maw of &thorn;at mayster: al &thorn;o mettes were,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn; dissches and dublers: wi&thorn; al &thorn;e dentees after.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
